TF BANK AB
(a limited liability company incorporated under the laws of the Kingdom of Sweden ("Sweden")
Offering of up to 10,400,625 ordinary shares
Price Range of €15 to €19

This is an offering (the "Offering") of up to 10,400,625 ordinary shares of TF Bank AB, a Swedish limited liability
company (the "Company" or "TF Bank" and, together with its consolidated subsidiaries, the "Group" or the "TF
Bank Group"), consisting of (i) up to 3,000,000 newly issued shares of the Company (the "New Shares"), (ii) up to
6,675,000 existing shares held by TFB Holding AB, the Company's majority shareholder, Jack Weil AB,
Förvaltningsaktiebolaget Segersta, Aktiebolaget Add Value, Gurrfinans AB, AB Monarda, KAAX Invest AB,
Tiberon AB, Mattias Carlsson, Pehr Petersson and Johannes Rintaniemi (the "Selling Shareholders") (the "Old
Shares"), and (iii) up to 725,625 existing shares made available via a share loan by the Selling Shareholders to cover
over-allotments (the "Greenshoe Shares" and together with the New Shares and the Old Shares, the "Offer
Shares"). The offer period will begin on 7 September 2015 and is expected to end on 16 September 2015 (the "Offer
Period"). The Offer Period may be extended or terminated at any time, but may not be shortened to before 14
September 2015.

The Offering consists of (i) a public offering to retail and institutional investors in the Federal Republic of Germany
("Germany") and (ii) private placements outside Germany and outside the United States of America (the "United
States" or the "U.S.") to selected institutional investors in reliance on Regulation S under the U.S. Securities Act of
1933, as amended (the "Securities Act"), and other applicable exemptions during the Offer Period.

On or about 16 September 2015, the Selling Shareholders and the Company will determine the final offer price per
Offer Share (the "Offer Price") and the final number of Offer Shares in consultation with the sole global coordinator
and sole bookrunner ICF BANK AG.

All 21,500,000 existing shares in the Company (the "Existing Shares") and the newly created shares (the Existing
Shares together with the newly created shares, the "Shares") are intended to be listed on the regulated market of the
Frankfurt Stock Exchange with simultaneous admission to the sub-segment of the regulated market with additional
post-admission obligations (Prime Standard) under the symbol "6TF". The Existing Shares are expected to commence
trading on or about 18 September 2015. Investors purchasing Offer Shares may start trading once the Existing Shares
commence trading. All of the Shares, including the Offer Shares, confer equal rights to dividends.

An investment in the Offer Shares involves a high degree of risk. See "Risk Factors" beginning on page 1 for
              certain risks to be considered in connection with investing in the Offer Shares.

The Shares are and will be, respectively, registered in the book-entry system maintained by Euroclear Sweden AB
("Euroclear Sweden"). No share certificates will be issued in respect of the Shares. The Offer Shares placed in the
Offering will be credited on or about 18 September 2015 to the accounts of investors through the book-entry facilities
of Clearstream Banking AG ("Clearstream"), Frankfurt am Main against payment. The International Securities
Identification Number (ISIN) for the Shares is SE0007331608 and the German Securities Code
(Wertpapierkennnummer – WKN) is A14XKR.

The Offer Shares have not been and will not be registered under the Securities Act or any U.S. state securities laws.
The Offer Shares may be offered and sold only outside the United States in accordance with Regulation S under the
Securities Act, and may not be offered, sold or delivered within the United States or to, or for the account or benefit
of, U.S. persons except pursuant to an exemption from, or in a transaction not subject to, the registration requirements
of the Securities Act. For a summary of the selling restrictions relating to the Offering, see "Selling Restrictions".

sequence. Even though an Element may be required to be inserted in the summary because of the type of securities
and issuer, it is possible that no relevant information can be given regarding the Element. In this case a brief
description of the point with "not applicable" is included.

                        market developments in the consumer finance industry and as a result of the increasing
                        importance of the Internet and smart phones, the Group refocused its business into pan-
                        European online and mobile banking and entered the e-commerce financing sector.

                        In 1998, the TF Bank Group made the decision to geographically expand its operations to
                        Finland and in 2002, to Norway and the Baltics. In 2013, the Group launched operations in
                        Poland and in 2014, expanded its online sales to Denmark. The Group is currently in the
                        process of launching its operations in the Czech Republic and Slovakia and is analyzing the
                        possibility of a market entry in the Netherlands, Lithuania, Austria, Germany and the UK. Due
                        to this geographic expansion, the TF Bank Group now operates in markets with a total
                        population of 85 million.

                        The TF Bank Group is structured into two distinct segments which both utilize the Group's IT
                        system and big data scoring models, but on different customer bases:

                                Direct Consumer Segment: In the direct consumer business segment (the "Direct
                                 Consumer Business Segment"), the Group principally offers unsecured loans to
                                 consumers up to €4,000 for individual applicants and up to €6,000 for joint loan
                                 applicants with a length of up to five years for personal usage (such as home
                                 improvements, holiday travel or the purchase of goods). In the last twelve months
                                 period ended 30 June (the "LTM Period", for further information on the LTM Period
                                 figures, see summary section B.7. below), the Direct Consumer Business Segment
                                 contributed 69.6% or €35.2 million to the Group's overall operating income. As at 30
                                 June 2015, the Group had €139.1 million in unsecured loans outstanding in this
                                 segment with an average loan value per customer of €2,055 in the LTM Period and an
                                 average length per loan, depending on the country of 16 to 19 months. The Group
                                 also offers savings accounts to retail customers in Sweden and Finland, with a total
                                 amount of €219.5 million in deposits as at 30 June 2015. With the acquisition of
                                 Norwegian finance company BB Finans ASA ("BB Finans"), the Group also gained
                                 the ability to offer credit cards to consumers and is in the process of initiating an
                                 expansion of this product to all its target countries.

Sales Finance & E-Commerce Segment: In the sales finance & e-commerce segment
(the "Sales Finance & E-Commerce Segment"), the Group offers merchant-tailored
invoice solutions (so-called "white label" solutions) and takes credit risk for
merchants by providing loan financing for end customers. In the LTM Period ended
30 June 2015, the Sales Finance & E-Commerce Segment contributed 30.4% or €15.4
million to the Group's overall operating income. As at 30 June 2015, the Group had
€38.5 million in loans outstanding to end customers. As at 30 June 2015, the average
loan amount per approved loan was €122 in the LTM Period and the average length
per loan, depending on the country, of nine to eleven months. The Sales Finance & E-
Commerce Segment had a total active customer base of 1,033,000 customers who
received loans since 1 January 2012 as of 30 June 2015 of which more than 830,000

or over 80% had an open balance outstanding in the LTM Period ended 30 June 2015.

As part of the Group's financial technology ("Fintech") strategy, the Group has started various
partnerships to increase its total active end customer base. In the Sales Finance & E-Commerce
Segment, it formed a joint venture ("Avarda") with Intrum Justitia AB ("Intrum Justitia"),
one of the leading credit management services companies in Europe. Intrum Justitia has
approximately 3,800 employees and is present in 20 European countries. Intrum Justitia's
shares are listed on the NASDAQ OMX Nordic large cap-segment list of companies. Avarda is
focused on Northern Europe (Sweden, Finland, Norway and Denmark) and offers flexible
online payment solutions for e-commerce merchants including white label invoice solutions
which allow merchants to utilize the Group's services and offer payment products to their
consumers under their own brand and tailored to their own needs. In the Direct Consumer
Business Segment, the Group recently partnered with SafeCharge Card Services Ltd.
("SafeCharge Card Services"), part of the SafeCharge Group to provide credit financings to

uer
                     Nordic retail customers as part of SafeCharge Card Service's online "digital wallet" and mobile
                     application solution utilizing the MasterCard ecosystem. The SafeCharge Group is a global
                     provider of payments services, technologies and risk management solutions for online and
                     mobile businesses and is listed on the London Stock Exchange. The Group has also partnered
                     with Odin Kapital AS ("Odin Kapital") through BB Finans in Norway, in order to provide
                     unsecured loans in the form of credit cards to dental patients. Other partnerships, which the
                     Group is currently negotiating in or in the process of preparing to launch are an e-commerce
                     financing solution for an online auction site in the Baltics and credit applications through
                     physical card payment terminals in the Baltics.

                     The Group's operating income in the LTM Period ended 30 June 2015 amounted to €50.6
                     million, and operating profit was €14.9 million with a return on equity of 35.6% and an
                     adjusted cost to income ratio of 35.3%. As at 30 June 2015, the Group had total deposits of
                     €219.5 million, total loans outstanding of €177.6 million and a CET1 capital ratio of 15.5%
                     and employed 77 employees (including nine employees at BB Finans, which was only acquired

        The Group has built up an IT and automatic scoring system based on a "big data"

       Online/Mobile banking: In recent years, major changes have taken place in European

       Growth in e-commerce: The proportion of consumers having made purchases using
        their phone or tablet increased strongly in the last several years in the markets in

       Changed credit behavior with credit needs in new sectors: The consumer credit
        market has undergone considerable development in recent years and currently
        represents an increasing part of people's day-to-day finances. Through the Internet the
        availability of consumer credit has increased and been simplified.

       The Swedish Financial Supervisory Authority has tightened capital requirements:
        The stricter requirements (which apply from 1 January 2015) entailed a requirement
        of at least 12% CET1 capital. A countercyclical capital buffer was introduced at 1%.
        On 27 June 2016, the SFSA will increase the countercyclical capital buffer to 1.5%.

The financial information summarized below is based on the consolidated financial statements
of the Company. The consolidated financial statements of the Company are included elsewhere
in this Prospectus. The consolidated financial statements for the year ended on 31 December
2014 were prepared in accordance with International Financial Reporting Standards, as
adopted in the EU ("IFRS"). These consolidated financial statements include comparative
figures for the year ended 31 December 2013 and 2012 prepared in accordance with IFRS.
The Prospectus includes unaudited consolidated financial information for the six months ended
30 June 2015 and 2014 and the LTM period ended 30 June 2015 that have been extracted from
the Company's unaudited interim condensed consolidated financial report as at and for the six-
month period ended 30 June 2015 prepared in accordance with IAS 34 – Interim Financial
Reporting ("IAS 34"). Any financial information in the following tables labeled as "audited"
has been taken from the Company's audited consolidated financial statements.

The Company believes the financial information for the LTM Period, as outlined below and
described elsewhere in the Prospectus, helps provide a more complete picture of the Group's
financial information because the Group's Sales Finance & E-Commerce Segment was only
incorporated into the Group beginning 1 May 2014, following its acquisition on 30 April 2014
from several companies within the Consortio Fashion Group (which is principally owned by
the Company's beneficial shareholders). The Sales Finance & E-Commerce Segment had not
been part of the Group for the preceding financial periods described herein. Therefore, the
LTM Period figures presented below show a true full year of the Group's results of operations,
including the Sales Finance & E-Commerce Segment. The LTM Period figures are derived by
adding the financial information for the six months ended 30 June 2015 and the year ended 31
December 2014 and subtracting the unaudited interim consolidated financial statements for
the six months ended 30 June 2014. The financial information for the twelve months ended 30
June 2015 is not necessarily indicative of the results that may be expected for the year ended
31 December 2015, and should not be used as the basis for or prediction of an annualized
calculation.

changes to the
issuer's         Net interest income increased from €19.1 million in the first six months of 2014 to €23.5
financial        million in the first six months of 2015. The principal reason for this increase was the growth in
condition and    interest income from the acquisition of the Sales Finance & E-Commerce Segment at the end
operating        of April 2014. As a result of the acquisition, net interest income for the Sales Finance & E-
results.         Commerce Segment of the Group increased from €2.2 million during the first half of 2014 to
                 €6.6 million during the first half of 2015, while net interest income in the Direct Consumer
                 Business Segment remained relatively stable. Interest expense decreased slightly from €2.1
                 million in the first six months of 2014 to €2.0 million for the same period in 2015 due to lower
                 interest rates on the Group's Swedish saving accounts.

                 Net interest income increased from €35.5 million in 2013 to €42.2 million in 2014. The
                 principal reason for this increase was the growth in interest income from €39.5 million in 2013
                 to €46.4 million in 2014. The increase resulted from the acquisition of the Sales Finance & E-
                 Commerce Segment at the end of April 2014. As a result of the acquisition, interest income of
                 €9.3 million for the period from 1 May 2014 to December 2014 was included in the Group's
                 interest income. In contrast, interest income in the Direct Consumer Business Segment
                 decreased from €39.5 million to €37.1 million principally due to the competitive environment

                 increase in loan applications in new markets such as Poland, the Group was still building up its

B. – Issuer
of direct consumer financial products. Interest expenses increased from €4.0 million to €4.2
million.
Interest expenses to
o the public decreased from €3.9 million to €3.7 million as
a
consequence of lowering the interest rates paid on deposits, even though deposit volumes
increased by €36.1 million from 31 December 2013 to 31 December 2014. Financial expenses

increased by €0.3 million as a result of swap rate differences between STIBOR and EURIBOR.

Net interest income increased from €33.3 million in 2012 to €35.5 million in 2013 principally
as a result of growth in interest income from €37.2 million in 2012 to €39.5 million in 2013.
The growth was principally due to positive business developments in Finland, while the growth
of the Group's Direct Consumer Business Segment was impacted by the competitive situation
in Sweden. Net interest expense increased from €3.8 million to €4.0 million. Interest expenses
to the public increased from €3.7 million to €3.9 million due to an increase in deposits of €24.6
million between 31 December 2012 and 31 December 2013.
Operating profit

Operating profit increased from €6.5 million in the first six months of 2014 to €7.5 million in
the first six months of 2015. This positive development was principally the result of the
integration of the Sales Finance & E-Commerce Segment into the TF Bank Group as at 1 May
2014 – in the first six months of 2014, only operational results in May and June of the
operating profit of the segment were included in the income statement of the Group. Operating
profit was negatively impacted by Avarda start-up costs in the first six months of 2015.
Additionally, there was a positive €0.4 million accounting effect in the first six months of 2014
in "other operating expenses".

Operating profit increased from €12.7 million in 2013 to €14.0 million in 2014. This increase
was principally the result of the integration of the Sales Finance & E-Commerce Segment into
the Group as at 1 May 2014.

Operating profit increased from €11.1 million in 2012 to €12.7 million in 2013. This was
principally the result of the Group's business growth and increased business development in its
target markets outside of Sweden.
Recent Developments

Recent Developments

                           On 29 December 2014, TF Bank entered into a share purchase agreement to acquire 100% of
                           the shares in the Norwegian company, BB Finans. The acquisition of BB Finans closed on 31
                           July 2015. For more information on BB Finans, see "Business—Material Contracts" and
                           "Business—Business Segments—Direct Consumer Business Segment."

                           On 18 August 2015, TF Bank entered into a revolving credit facility agreement with BB
                           Finans, whereby the Company agreed to advance BB Finans up to the lesser of NOK 200
                           million (approximately €22 million) or an amount equal to 80% of the net receivables of BB
                           Finans, in order to reduce its financing costs and increase its liquidity. As of the date of this
                           Prospectus, the Company had advanced NOK 100 million (approximately €11 million) to BB
                           Finans under the terms of this revolving credit facility. This agreement expires on 18 August
                           2017.

Other risks and uncertainties which are presently unknown to the Group could also have

The Group's operations and industry are in particular subject to the following risks:

   An economic slowdown could adversely affect the demand for the Group's direct
    consumer business or sales finance products or increase its credit losses and decrease its
    growth.
   A simultaneous withdrawal of savings deposits by a large number of the Group's
    customers or a lack of sufficient cash inflows from its business operations could result in
    a liquidity shortage which could negatively affect the Group's ability to maintain or grow
    its business.
   The Group may not be able to successfully evaluate the creditworthiness of its customers
    or may not price its direct consumer business or sales finance products correctly.
   The Group's growth strategy to a significant extent relies on its sales finance business and
    the joint venture Avarda with credit management service provider Intrum Justitia.
   The Group may not be able to effectively integrate BB Finans and grow the credit card
    business of BB Finans in line with its growth strategy.
   The Group may fail to successfully leverage its various partnerships such as the Group's
    partnership with SafeCharge Card Services.
   The Group's business and results of operations may be adversely affected if the Group is
    unable to manage its growth effectively.
   Any disruption in the Group's information systems or the global telecommunication
    infrastructure could adversely affect the Group's operations.
   The Group is partially dependent on third party suppliers and material agreements with
    third parties.
   If the Group loses current key members of management or is unable to attract and retain
    the talent required for its business, the Group's business may suffer.
   The Group's operations are subject to exchange rate risk.
   The Group is subject to accounting and management risk.
   The Group is subject to certain risks connected to interest rate fluctuations.
   The Group's business is dependent on the license to conduct banking business.
   Changes in the Swedish Deposit Protection Program, or a decision resulting in the savings
    deposit accounts with the Company no longer being covered by the Deposit Protection
    Program, may have a negative effect on the Group.
   The Company may fail to comply with all regulations it is subject to and such failures
    could materially impact its operations and strategy.

The Company's shares, which include all 21,500,000 existing shares in the Company and the
newly created shares (the "Shares") are subject to the following key risks:
   The absence of a prior public trading for the Shares may seriously impact the liquidity and
    trading price of the Shares.
   The market price of the Shares may be volatile.
   Future capitalization measures could lead to a substantial dilution, i.e., a reduction in the
    value of the Shares and the control rights of existing shareholders' interests in the Group.
   Shareholders are subject to the risk of detrimental changes of foreign exchange rates and
    adverse tax consequences.
   The Group's ability to pay dividends in the future depends on several factors, including

Im Rahmen der Strategie der Gruppe auf dem Gebiet der Finanztechnologie
("Fintech") ist die Gruppe verschiedene Partnerschaften eingegangen, um ihren
aktiven Kundenstamm zu vergrößern. Im Geschäftssegment Sales Finance & E-
Commerce hat sie mit Intrum Justitia AB ("Intrum Justitia"), einem führenden
Anbieter von Kredit-Management-Services in Europa, ein Joint Venture gegründet
("Avarda"). Intrum Justitia hat ca. 3.800 Mitarbeiter und ist in 20 europäischen
Ländern vertreten. Die Aktien von Intrum Justitia sind an der NASDAQ OMX
Nordic im Large Cap Segment notiert. Avarda ist schwerpunktmäßig in Nordeuropa
(Schweden, Finnland, Norwegen und Dänemark) tätig und bietet flexible Lösungen
für Online-Zahlungen für E-Commerce-Händler an, insbesondere auch "white
label"-Lösungen, mit denen die Händler die Dienstleistungen der Gruppe in
Anspruch nehmen und ihren Kunden Zahlungsmöglichkeiten unter ihrer eigenen
Marke anbieten können, die speziell auf ihre Bedürfnisse zugeschnitten sind. Im
Geschäftssegment Direct Consumer Business arbeitet die Gruppe seit kurzem mit
SafeCharge Card Service's Ltd. ("SafeCharge Card Services") zusammen, einem
Unternehmen        der      SafeCharge Gruppe,        mit     dem      zusammen
Darlehensfinanzierungen für Endverbraucher in den nordischen Ländern angeboten
werden sollen, wobei über das "digital wallet" und die mobile App von SafeCharge
Card Services auf das MasterCard System zurückgegriffen wird. Die SafeCharge
Gruppe ist ein weltweit tätiger Anbieter von Dienstleistungen in den Bereichen
Zahlungsverkehr, Technologie und Risikomanagement im Online- und Mobil-App-
Geschäft und ist an der Londoner Börse notiert. Außerdem ist die Gruppe über BB
Finans in Norwegen eine Zusammenarbeit mit Odin Kapital AS ("Odin Kapital")
eingegangen, in deren Rahmen unbesicherte Darlehen in Form von Kreditkarten an
Zahnarztpatienten ausgegeben werden. Andere Kooperationen, die von der Gruppe
gerade verhandelt oder vorbereitet werden und im Baltikum zum Einsatz kommen
sollen, sind eine E-Commerce-Finanzierungslösung für eine Online-Auktionsseite
und Kreditanträge über elektronische Zahlungsterminals.

B. – Emittentin

zugerechnet. Im Gegenzug sank die Summe des Betriebsergebnisses des
Geschäftssegments Direct Consumer Business hauptsächlich aufgrund des
Wettbewerbs in dem entsprechenden schwedischen Markt von € 39,5 Mio. auf
€ 37,1 Mio. Trotz eines erheblichen Anstiegs der Darlehensanträge in neuen
Märkten wie beispielsweise Polen, Folge der geografischen Ausweitung des
Geschäfts der Gruppe, arbeitet die Gruppe noch am Aufbau ihrer Datenbank für
diese Märkte und hat daher die Bewilligungsquote für Darlehen niedrig gehalten,
was das Gesamtvolumen der Produkte im Bereich Consumer Business beeinflusste.
Der Zinsaufwand ist von € 4,0 Mio. auf € 4,2 Mio. gestiegen. Der Zinsaufwand für
Spareinlagen fiel von € 3,9 Mio. auf € 3,7 Mio. obwohl das Spareinlagenvolumen
um €36,1 Mio. zwischen dem 31. Dezember 2013 und dem 31. Dezember 2014
gestiegen ist. Der sinkende Zinsaufwand wurde durch Aufwand in Höhe von € 0,3
Mio. wegen Differenzen zwischen den Zinssätzen für das Interbankengeschäft
STIBOR und EURIBOR ausgeglichen.

Hauptsächlich aufgrund des Anstiegs der Zinserträge von € 37,2 Mio. 2012 auf
€ 39,5 Mio. 2013 ist der Zinsüberschuss von € 33,3 Mio. in 2012 auf € 35,5 Mio. in
2013 gestiegen. Das Wachstum war vorwiegend auf gute Geschäfte in Finnland
zurückzuführen, während das Wachstum im Geschäftssegment Direct Consumer
Business der Gruppe aufgrund der Wettbewerbssituation in Schweden
beeinträchtigt wurde. Der Zinsaufwand hat sich von € 3,8 Mio. auf € 4,0 Mio.
verbessert. Der Zinsaufwand für Spareinlagen ist aufgrund einer Änderung der
Unterschiede zwischen den Swap-Sätzen und aufgrund eines Anstiegs des
Spareinlagenvolumens um € 24,6 Mio. vom 31. Dezember 2012 bis 31. Dezember
2013 von € 3,7 Mio. auf € 3,9 Mio. gestiegen.
Betriebsgewinn

Der Betriebsgewinn ist von € 6,5 Mio. in den ersten sechs Monaten des Jahres 2014
auf € 7,5 Mio. in den ersten sechs Monaten des Jahres 2015 gestiegen. Diese
positive Entwicklung war vorwiegend auf die Integration des Geschäftssegments
Sales Finance & E-Commerce in die TF Bank Gruppe zum 1. Mai 2014
zurückzuführen. In den ersten sechs Monaten des Jahres 2014 war nur der
Betriebsgewinn dieses Segments für die Monate Mai und Juni in der Gewinn- und
Verlustrechnung der Gruppe enthalten. Zusätzlich waren in den ersten sechs
Monaten des Jahres 2014 bei den "sonstigen betrieblichen Aufwendungen" positive
buchmäßige Auswirkungen in Höhe von € 0,4 Mio zu verzeichnen.

Der Betriebsgewinn ist von € 12,7 Mio. im Jahr 2013 auf €14,0 Mio. im Jahr 2014
gestiegen. Dieser Anstieg war insbesondere auf die Integration des
Geschäftssegments Sales Finance & E-Commerce zum 1. Mai 2014 in die Gruppe
zurückzuführen.

Der Betriebsgewinn ist von € 11,1 Mio. im Jahr 2012 auf € 12,7 Mio. im Jahr 2013
gestiegen. Dies war insbesondere auf das Geschäftswachstum der Gruppe und die
Expansion in den Zielmärkten außerhalb von Schweden zurückzuführen.

beschriebenen Risiken sind nicht die einzigen Risiken, denen die Gruppe
ausgesetzt ist. Andere Risiken und Unwägbarkeiten, die der Gruppe derzeit
nicht bekannt sind, könnten ebenfalls erhebliche negative Auswirkungen auf
die Geschäfts-, Finanz- und Ertragslage der Gruppe haben.

Für die Tätigkeit der Gruppe und der Branche bestehen insbesondere die
folgenden Risiken:

   Eine Abschwächung der Konjunktur könnte sich negativ auf die
    Nachfrage nach Verbraucherdarlehen und Teilzahlungskrediten der
    Gruppe auswirken, ihre Kreditverluste erhöhen und ihr Wachstum
    reduzieren.

   Eine zeitgleiche Entnahme von Spareinlagen durch eine große Zahl von
    Kunden, oder geringe Mittelzuflüsse aus den Geschäften der Gruppe
    könnten Liquiditätsengpässe zur Folge haben, was den Geschäftsbetrieb
    der Gruppe oder dessen Erweiterung beeinträchtigen könnte.

   Es besteht die Möglichkeit, dass die Gruppe die Kreditwürdigkeit ihrer
    Kunden nicht richtig bewertet oder dass ihre Preisgestaltung bei
    Produkten, die sie im Rahmen des Verbraucher- oder
    Teilzahlungskreditgeschäfts anbietet, unrichtig ist.

   Die Wachstumsstrategie der Gruppe ist insbesondere an das Sales
    Finance-Geschäft und das Joint Venture Avarda mit dem Kredit-
    Management-Servicesanbieter Intrum Justitia gebunden.

   Es besteht die Möglichkeit, dass der Gruppe eine erfolgreiche
    Integration der BB Finans nicht gelingt und dass das
    Kreditkartengeschäft der BB Finans sich nicht so entwickelt, wie in der
    Wachstumsstrategie vorgesehen.

   Möglicherweise gelingt es der Gruppe nicht, ihre diversen
    Kooperationen, wie beispielsweise die Zusammenarbeit mit SafeCharge
    Card Services, erfolgreich zu nutzen.
