THE OFFERING
Subject Matter of the Offering

The Offering (including any potential over-allotment) relates to the sale of up to 10,400,625 ordinary
shares with a quota value of SEK 5.00 per share, consisting of:

up to 3,000,000 New Shares by the Company;

up to 6,675,000 Old Shares held by the Selling Shareholders; and

up to 725,625 Greenshoe Shares made available via a share loan by the Selling Shareholders to
cover over-allotments.

To enable settlement of the New Shares sold in the Offering, the Selling Shareholders (via TFB Holding
AB) will lend up to 3,000,000 shares from their existing shareholding to ICF BANK AG in its role as
settlement agent by transferring these shares to a trust account. The New Shares will be created and
registered with the SCRO as soon as practical after the settlement.

If the maximum number of Offer Shares are placed with investors, the Offer Shares will after the
completion of the Offering represent approximately 39.5% of all the shares in the Company assuming the
Greenshoe Option is not exercised (42.5% if the Greenshoe Option is exercised). In the event that less
than the maximum number of Offer Shares are placed with investors, the Company and the Selling
Shareholders have agreed that preference will be given to the placement of New Shares.

The Offering consists of a public offering of the Offer Shares in the Federal Republic of Germany and
private placements of the Offer Shares in certain jurisdictions outside the Federal Republic of Germany
and outside of the United States of America in reliance on Regulation S under the Securities Act.

The Underwriters are ICF BANK AG, M.M.Warburg & CO (AG & Co.) KGaA and DZ BANK AG
Deutsche Zentral-Genossenschaftsbank, Frankfurt am Main.
Price Range and Offer Period

The price range within which purchase orders may be placed is €15 to €19 per Offer Share (the "Price
Range"). The Company and the Selling Shareholders may, in consultation with ICF BANK AG, change
the Price Range.

The Offer Period, during which investors may submit purchase orders for the Offer Shares, is expected to
begin on 7 September 2015 and is expected to end on 16 September 2015, at 17:00 CET (Central
European Time) for private investors (natural persons) and for institutional investors. The Company and
the Selling Shareholders may, in consultation with ICF BANK AG, extend, shorten or terminate the Offer
Period. However, the Offer Period may not be shortened to before 14 September 2015. An extension,
shortening or termination of the Offer Period will be announced by means of an ad-hoc release on an
electronic information system and on the Company's website. Purchase orders must be denominated in
full numbers of shares. Purchase orders may be limited within the price range (price-steps of euro 0.10
will be accepted). There is no minimum or maximum amount for orders. Investors will not be allocated
fractional amounts of shares.

The Company and the Selling Shareholders reserve the right, in consultation with ICF BANK AG, to
increase or decrease the total number of Offer Shares (including decreases and increases of the number of
New Shares and Old Shares) and to change the Price Range.

Changes in the number of Offer Shares, a narrowing of the Price Range, or the extension or shortening of
the Offer Period will not invalidate any purchase orders that have already been submitted. In case of a
narrowing of the Price Range, the Company will issue a press release in order to inform investors about
such change. In case the Price Range is extended on the lower or upper range, or the final offer price is
outside the Price Range, a supplement to this Prospectus is required to be published (see also "–
Cancellation Rights" below).
Subscription for Offer Shares in the Public Offering in Germany

As part of the public offering in Germany, investors who wish to submit offers to purchase Offer Shares
may, within the Offer Period, submit them via their depositary bank that manages their security account
directly to ICF BANK AG. ICF BANK AG as sole bookrunner will consider all orders received until the
end of the Offer Period.
Pricing and Allotment

After the expiration of the Offer Period, the offer price and the final number of Offer Shares placed in the
Offering will be determined by the Company and the Selling Shareholders in consultation with the sole
global arranger and sole bookrunner, ICF BANK AG. The price will be set on the basis of the purchase
orders submitted by investors during the Offer Period (both from investors submitting orders in the public
offering in Germany and institutional investors submitting orders outside of Germany) that have been
collated in the order book prepared during the bookbuilding process. Price-setting is expected to occur on
or about 16 September 2015. These orders will be evaluated according to the prices offered and the
investment horizons of the respective investors. This method of setting the number of shares that will be
placed at the offer price is, in principle, aimed at maximizing proceeds. Consideration will also be given
to whether the offer price and the number of shares to be placed allow for the reasonable expectation that
the share price will demonstrate steady performance in the secondary market given the demand for the
Shares noted in the order book. Attention will be paid not only to the prices offered by investors and the
number of investors wanting shares at a particular price, but also to the composition of the group of
shareholders in the Company that would result at a given price, and expected investor behavior. For
further information regarding allotment criteria, see "–Allotment Criteria". The Company and the Selling
Shareholders will not specifically charge any expenses and taxes related to the offering to investors.

After the offer price has been set, the Offer Shares will be allotted to investors on the basis of the offers to
purchase then available. The offer price and the final number of Offer Shares placed in the Offering (that
is, the result of the Offering) are expected to be published on or about 16 September 2015 by means of an
ad-hoc release on an electronic information system and on the Company's website. Investors who have
placed orders to purchase Offer Shares can obtain information from the Underwriters about the offer price
and the number of Offer Shares allotted to them on the business day following the setting of the offer
price. A purchase agreement between the investor and the Underwriters on the allotted Offer Shares will
be executed once the shares are allotted. These purchase agreements are contingent on the execution of
the Underwriting Agreement, which may be terminated by the Underwriters before settlement.

Commencement of trading (Aufnahme des Handels) of the Existing Shares on the regulated market
segment (regulierter Markt) of the Frankfurt Stock Exchange (Frankfurter Wertpapierbörse) is expected
to occur on 18 September 2015.

Should the placement volume prove insufficient to satisfy all orders placed at the offer price, the
Underwriters reserve the right to reject orders, or to accept them only in part.
Cancellation Rights

Purchase orders are binding and irrevocable, and may only be cancelled if applicable laws and regulations
provide for a cancellation right.

In accordance with the Swedish Financial Instruments Trading Act, the Company will be obliged until
start of trading of the Shares begins on or about 18 September 2015, to issue a supplement to the
Prospectus in case a new circumstance, factual error or omission in the Prospectus is discovered, if such
new circumstance, factual error or omission may bear significance to the investors. Such supplement will
be published in the same manner as the Prospectus.

Investors who have placed purchase orders for Offer Shares before the publication of a supplement to the
Prospectus may choose to cancel their purchase orders. The cancellation right must be exercised within a
cancellation period which may not be shorter than two banking days from the publication of the
supplement to the Prospectus. An investor's cancellation of a purchase order will be deemed to be made in
respect of all the purchase orders of that investor. A precondition for the right to cancel is that the new
circumstance, factual error or omission arose or was noted before the delivery of the Offer Shares.
Cancellations must be filed with the Underwriter with which the purchase order was placed or via the

investor's depository bank if the order is initially placed via the XETRA-trading system. Information on
the right to cancel shall be issued in the correction or supplement.

The publication of a supplement to the Prospectus and the right to cancel purchase orders will be
announced by means of an ad-hoc release on an electronic information system and on the Company's
website. Investors who have submitted offers to purchase will not be notified individually. The
supplement to the Prospectus will state the last date for cancellation of a purchase order or consent.
Termination/cancellation of the Offering before Settlement

The Company and the Selling Shareholders, in consultation with ICF BANK AG, may cancel the
Offering at any time before pricing and allocation of the Offer Shares. Under certain conditions the
Underwriters may also terminate the Underwriting Agreement relating to the Offering entered into with
the Company and the Selling Shareholders on 4 September 2015 after pricing and allocation and before
the settlement of the Offering. If the Offering is cancelled, investors will not receive any Offer Shares and
will not be required to pay the Offer Price in relation to such Offer Shares.
Settlement

The Shares allocated to investors are expected to be credited to the accounts of investors after completion
of the Offering on 18 September 2015 against payment of the offer price. The delivery of the Offer Shares
will, at the investor's option, be made to a securities deposit account maintained by a German bank with
Clearstream Banking AG or to a securities account of a participant in Euroclear Bank SA/NV, 1,
Boulevard Roi Albert II, 1120 Brussels, Belgium, as the operator of the Euroclear system, or to
Clearstream Banking, société anonyme, 42 Avenue JF Kennedy, 1855 Luxembourg, Grand Duchy of
Luxembourg, for the account of such shareholder.
Shareholder Rights

The Offer Shares delivered to investors confer full shareholder rights in the Company upon delivery. The
New Shares will confer full shareholder rights in the Company upon registration with the SCRO. All of
the Shares, including the Offer Shares, confer equal rights to dividends.
Registration of New Shares; No Pre-emptive Subscription Right of the Existing Shareholders

The Swedish Companies Act requires the full subscription price for new shares to be received by the
company in order to register those new shares with the SCRO. The New Shares are expected to be
registered with the SCRO promptly after 18 September 2015. Of the subscription price for the New
Shares, SEK 5.00 per share will be recorded in the share capital and the remainder in the unrestricted
equity reserve. To facilitate settlement of all Offered Shares on 18 September 2015, the Selling
Shareholders have provided a total of 3,000,000 shares from their holdings to ICF BANK AG to an
escrow account with permission granted to ICF BANK AG to use the shares in accordance with the
allocation settings to fulfill obligations towards investors. Once the New Shares are registered, these
shares will be provided to the Selling Shareholders in fulfillment of this share loan.

On 4 June 2015, an extraordinary general meeting of shareholders of the Company authorized the Board
of Directors to resolve on issuing up to 64,500,000 shares in the Company. The Board of Directors is
authorized to resolve on all the terms and conditions of the share issue. The authorization stays in force
until annual meeting of shareholders of the Company to be held in 2016.

When the Offer Price has been finally determined, the Board of Directors will resolve to issue the New
Shares pursuant to an authorization of the shareholders' meeting convened on 4 June 2015 and a
shareholders' meeting the same day will approve such resolution. The New Shares issued in the Offering
are issued in a directed share issue, i.e., the New Shares will be offered in deviation of the pre-emptive
subscription right of the existing shareholders of the Company. The grounds for deviating from the pre-
emptive subscription right are the funding of the Company's business and the broadening of its
shareholder base necessary for a planned listing of the Shares in the Company on the Frankfurt Stock
Exchange.

Allotment Criteria

The allotment of Offer Shares to retail investors will be made on a non-discriminatory basis (however
such retail investors may be treated differently based on the size of orders placed). Allotments of Offer
Shares to non-retail investors who placed orders with the Underwriters directly will be made on the basis
of the quality of the individual investors and individual orders and other important allotment criteria to be
determined by the Company and the Selling Shareholders after consultation with ICF BANK AG.
Stabilization Measures, Over-Allotments and Greenshoe Option

In connection with the placement of the Offer Shares, ICF BANK AG or its affiliates will act as the
stabilization manager and may, as stabilization manager, and acting in accordance with legal requirements
(Section 20a (3) of the German Securities Trading Act (Wertpapierhandelsgesetz – "WpHG") in
conjunction with Commission Regulation (EC) No. 2273/2003 of 22 December 2003), make over-
allotments and take stabilization measures to support the market price of the Shares and thereby
counteract any selling pressure. The stabilization manager is under no obligation to take any stabilization
measures. Stabilization measures may not be carried out above the offer price for the Offer Shares. No
assurance can therefore be provided that any stabilization measures will be taken. Where stabilization
measures are taken, these may be terminated at any time without notice. Such measures may be taken
from the date the shares of the Company are listed on the regulated market on the Frankfurt Stock
Exchange and must be terminated no later than the thirtieth calendar day after this date (the
"Stabilization Period").

These measures may result in the market price of the Shares being higher than would otherwise have been
the case. Moreover, the market price may temporarily be at an unsustainable level. Under the possible
stabilization measures, investors may, in addition to the 9,675,000 Old Shares and New Shares being
offered, be allocated up to 725,625 additional Shares, from the Selling Shareholders' holdings as part of
the allocation of the shares to be placed ("Over-Allotment"), however only if the Offering is
oversubscribed. For the purpose of a possible Over-Allotment, ICF BANK AG, for the account of the
Underwriters, will be provided with up to 725,625 Shares from the holdings of the Selling Shareholders
in the form of a securities loan of shares to an escrow account with permission granted to ICF BANK AG
to use the shares in accordance with the allocation settings to fulfill obligations towards investors as part
of the over-allotment of shares; this number of shares will not exceed 7.5% of the sum of the New Shares
and the Existing Shares.

In addition, the Selling Shareholders (via TFB Holding AB) will grant the Underwriters an option to
acquire the borrowed shares at the offer price less agreed commissions. This Greenshoe Option will
terminate 30 calendar days after the commencement of the stock exchange trading of the shares.

The stabilization manager is entitled to exercise the Greenshoe Option to the extent over-allotments of
Shares were initially made; the number of Shares is to be reduced by the number of Shares held by the

stabilization manager as at the date on which the Greenshoe Option is exercised and that were acquired by
the stabilization manager in the context of stabilization measures.

Once the Stabilization Period has ended, an announcement will be made within one week in various
media outlets distributed across the entire European Economic Area as to whether stabilization measures
were taken, when price stabilization started and finished, and the price range within which stabilization
was taken; the latter will be made known for each occasion on which price stabilization measures were
taken. Exercise of the Greenshoe Option, the timing of its exercise and the number and type of shares
concerned will also be announced promptly in the same manner.
Dilution of New Investors

As at 30 June 2015, the Company had 21,500,000 shares and a total equity of €35.7 million which means
that the total equity per share was €1.66. After giving effect to the creation of 3,000,000 New Shares
(which will occur as soon as practicable after 18 September 2015) at an offer price of €17 per New Share,
being the mid-point of the Price Range, the Group's total equity as at 30 June 2015 would have been
€83.6 million (which means the total equity per share – including the New Shares – will be €3.41), after
deducting expected underwriting commissions and estimated offering expenses payable by the Company.
This represents a dilution in shareholders' equity of €13.59, or 79.9% per share to investors purchasing
Offer Shares.

Registration of the Shares

The Company is a Swedish public limited company that intends to apply to the Frankfurt Stock Exchange
to have its Shares listed. To facilitate the trading on the Frankfurt Stock Exchange, the Shares in the
Company will be registered in the electronic book-entry securities system maintained by Euroclear
Sweden. The Company and its Shares will have their primary registration in the book-entry register of
Euroclear Sweden. Furthermore, Shares admitted to trading on Frankfurt Stock Exchange will be
registered in the corresponding German book-entry securities system maintained by Clearstream.

Clearstream will be entered into the shareholder register maintained by Euroclear Sweden through a
nominee account that will be held by SEB, of the Shares traded on Frankfurt Stock Exchange, and it will
duplicate (mirror) the entry for these Shares in the book-entry securities system of Clearstream. Shares
registered in the system of Clearstream will have the same ISIN as the Shares registered in Euroclear
Sweden.
Inclusion to Trading

The application for inclusion of the Existing Shares to trading in the Prime Standard (regulated market)
on the Frankfurt Stock Exchange was made on 4 September 2015. The Frankfurt Stock Exchange is
expected to approve the inclusion of the Existing Shares to trading on 17 September 2015. If approval is
granted, the Existing Shares are expected to begin trading on the Frankfurt Stock Exchange on 18
September 2015. The New Shares are expected to be approved for inclusion to trading after 18 September
2015. All investors purchasing Offer Shares in the Offering will be able to trade these shares when the
Existing Shares start trading on the Frankfurt Stock Exchange.
ISIN/WKN/stock symbol
Designated Sponsor

ICF BANK AG has agreed to assume the function of a designated sponsor of the Shares traded on the
Frankfurt Stock Exchange for a period of at least two years. Pursuant to the designated sponsor agreement
expected to be concluded among ICF BANK AG and the Company, ICF BANK AG will, among other
things, place limited buy and sell orders for the Shares in the electronic trading system of the Frankfurt
Stock Exchange during regular trading hours. This is intended to achieve greater liquidity in the market
for the shares.
Other Legal Relationships between the Company and Interested Parties

The Underwriters have entered into a contractual relationship with the Company in connection with the
Offering of the Offer Shares. The Company has engaged ICF BANK AG, M.M.Warburg & CO (AG &
Co.) KGaA and DZ BANK AG Deutsche Zentral-Genossenschaftsbank, Frankfurt am Main to serve as
Underwriters. Upon successful execution of the Offering, the Underwriters will receive a commission.
The Underwriters or companies affiliated with them may from time to time enter into business

relationships with companies of the Group or perform services on their behalf as part of their normal
course of business.

The Selling Shareholders will receive the proceeds from offering the Old Shares and the Greenshoe
Shares, if the Greenshoe Option is exercised.
REASONS FOR THE OFFERING AND USE OF PROCEEDS

The Company will receive the proceeds from the sale of 3,000,000 New Shares after deducting the costs
of the Offering including Underwriters' fees and commissions. Assuming offer proceeds for all New
Shares of €51 million based on a price of €17 per Offer Share (based on the middle of the price range),
the total costs attributable to the Company of the Offering including Underwriters' fees and commissions
for the New Shares are estimated to be €3.1 million and net proceeds would be €47.9 million. The Selling
Shareholders and the Company will bear the costs relating to the fees and commissions of the
Underwriters for the shares they are selling. The Company will be responsible for all other documented,
reasonable costs and expenses of the Underwriters incurred in connection with the Offering.

The Group plans to utilize the net proceeds to (i) support the Group's organic growth in the markets where
the Group is already present, (ii) fund the further geographic expansion into new markets as part of the
Group's strategy to become a pan-European online and mobile bank, (iii) support the Group's product
expansion, such as its credit card offering, (iv) leverage the Group's existing partnering relationships and
invest in new partnerships, and (v) for general corporate purposes.

The Company has not yet adopted any resolutions on the potential use of the proceeds received by
conducting the public offering. The timing to implement the potential uses above, as well as their costs,
cannot be firmly established at this time.

The Company has thus far paid out dividends in amounts of €128,000 in 2012, €148,000 in 2013, €94,000

Presentation of Financial Information
Historical financial information

In addition, this Prospectus includes unaudited consolidated financial information for the six months

The Audited Consolidated Financial Statements were audited by PricewaterhouseCoopers AB, SE-405 32
Göteborg, Sweden as principal auditor ("PwC") and are each provided with an unqualified audit opinion.
PwC is a member of the Swedish professional accounting association Föreningen Auktoriserade

The Company has appointed PwC, as the auditor for the financial period ending 31 December 2015.

Where financial information in this Prospectus is referred to as "audited", the information was taken from

Non-IFRS measures

The Company has included certain non-IFRS financial measures in this Prospectus. The management of
the Company believes that these non-IFRS financial measures provide meaningful supplemental
information to both the management and the investors regarding their performance by excluding items
that may not be indicative of the operating results of the underlying business. These non-IFRS financial
measures should not be viewed in isolation or as substitutes to the equivalent IFRS measures, but should
be used in conjunction with the most directly comparable IFRS measures in the reported results.

The Company has included in the Prospectus the adjusted cost/income ratio, return on equity, return on
business equity, credit volume, CET1 ratio and net loan loss ratio that are not accounting measures
defined under IFRS. These measures should not be considered as an alternative to (a) operating profit or
profit/loss for the period as a measure of operating performance, (b) cash flows from operating, investing,
and financing activities as a measure of their abilities to meet their cash need or (c) any other measures of
performance under IFRS. Management believes that these measures are useful indicators of an entity's
ability to obtain financing and service its debt and can assist certain investors, security analysts and other
interested parties in evaluating the business.

Because all companies do not calculate adjusted cost/income ratios, return on equity, return on business
equity, net loan loss ratio and credit volume on a consistent basis, the presentation of these key
performance indicators in the Prospectus may not be comparable to measures under the same or similar
names used by other companies. Accordingly, undue reliance should not be placed on these items in this
Prospectus.

MANAGEMENT'S DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS OF FINANCIAL CONDITION AND
                    RESULTS OF OPERATIONS

The following discussion should be read in conjunction with the Audited Consolidated Financial
Statements included elsewhere in this Prospectus as well as other financial information included in this
Prospectus and "Selected Financial and Operating Information." The discussion below includes an
analysis of the Group's financial condition and historical results of operations. It also includes
descriptions of certain factors that have affected, and may continue to affect the Group's business, results
of operations, and financial condition. The impact of these and other potential factors may vary
significantly in the future.

In addition, the following discussion includes forward-looking statements, which, although based on
assumptions that the Group considers reasonable, are subject to risks and uncertainties that could cause
actual events or conditions to differ materially from those expressed or implied by the forward-looking
statements. For a discussion of some of those risks and uncertainties, see "General Information –
Forward-looking statements" and "Risk Factors."

Any financial information in the following tables labeled as "audited" has been taken from the Audited
Consolidated Financial Statements. Any other financial information in the following tables labeled as
"unaudited" has not been taken from those Audited Consolidated Financial Statements.

Figures presented in this Prospectus are commercially rounded up or down to whole euro, thousands of
euro or millions of euro. All percentages are commercially rounded up or down and are based on
reported unrounded numbers included in the Audited Consolidated Financial Statements. Due to
rounding, the sum of the individually rounded figures may not equal the rounded total figure in all cases.
Accordingly, in certain instances, the sum of the numbers in a column or row in tables may not conform
exactly to the total figure given for that column or row.
Introduction

The TF Bank Group is an online bank which offers consumer finance products directly to retail customers
and offers e-commerce solutions to merchants in seven countries in Northern Europe, the Baltics and
Central and Eastern Europe. As at 30 June 2015, the Group had a total of 1.1 million active customers in
its two segments and a combined 2.2 million of user profiles for scoring in its database. The Group was
granted a banking license from the Swedish regulator SFSA in 2012, allowing the Group to offer banking
services in the entire European Economic Area. The Group's banking services include unsecured loans,
credit cards and savings accounts for retail customers which are insured by the Swedish Deposit
Protection Program. The Group uses various distribution channels to market its products, including
through partnerships and physical payment terminals.

The Group's banking services include unsecured loans,credit cards and savings accounts for retail customers which are insured by the Swedish DepositProtection Program. The Group uses various distribution channels to market its products, includingthrough partnerships and physical payment terminals.

blobs.text:
The Company, as an incorporated entity, started its Direct Consumer Business in 1987, offering mail
order customers the opportunity to borrow money for purposes other than catalogue purchases. In the
mid-2000s to late 2000s, the Company under new management and ownership began refocusing its
business towards online banking products. Following the market developments in the consumer finance
industry and as a result of the increasing importance of the Internet and smart phones, the Group
refocused its business into pan-European online and mobile banking and entered the e-commerce
financing sector.

In 1998, the TF Bank Group made the decision to geographically expand its operations to Finland and in
2002, to Norway and the Baltics. In 2013, the Group launched operations in Poland and in 2014,
expanded its online sales to Denmark. The Group is currently in the process of launching its operations in
the Czech Republic and Slovakia and is analyzing the possibility of a market entry in Austria, Germany
and the UK. Due to this geographic expansion, the TF Bank Group now operates in markets with a total
population of 85 million.

The Group's total operating income in the LTM Period ended 30 June 2015 amounted to €50.6 million,
and operating profit was €14.9 million with a return on equity of 35.6% and an adjusted cost to income
ratio of 35.3%. As at 30 June 2015, the Group had total deposits of €219.5 million, total loans to the
public outstanding of €177.6 million (after provision for expected loan losses) and a CET1 capital ratio of
15.5% and employed 77 employees (including nine employees at BB Finans, which was acquired in July
2015).
Key Factors Affecting the Group's Results of Operations

The Company management believes that the following factors have affected the Group's results of
operations in the past three fiscal years and in 2015, and may continue to affect its business, results of
operations, and financial condition. The impact of these and other factors may vary significantly in the
future.

E-Commerce Growth in Europe, especially in Sales Finance, the integration of the Sales Finance &
E-Commerce Segment and the Group's Avarda Partnership

key_factor_affecting_results: E-Commerce Growth in Europe, especially in Sales Finance, the integration of the Sales Finance &E-Commerce Segment and the Group's Avarda Partnership

blobs.text:
In the Group's Sales Finance & E-Commerce Segment, it operates in the fast growing and competitive
sales finance sector. Growth rates in the e-commerce sector in Europe are estimated to be 20% on average
in 2015. Online consumers in Europe are expected to make more online transactions, with an average of
17.8 online transactions per customer expected in 2015 compared to 15.8 in 2014. As at 2014, the Nordic
countries have approximately 15.7 million consumers shopping online. Annual online sales in Central
Europe grew on average by 20% from 2010 to 2014 and there is a general high growth potential in e-
commerce in Central and Eastern European markets in which the Group has recently expanded. Poland,
with a population of 38 million, had only 9.6 million consumers shopping online (25% of the population)
in 2013, the Czech Republic, with a population of 10.5 million, had only 3.5 million consumers shopping
online (33% of the population) in 2013 and the Baltics, with a population of 6.3 million, had only 1.1
million consumers shopping online (16% of the population) in 2013. See "Market Information – the Sales
Finance & E-Commerce Market" for more information on market data and sources for this market data.

The Sales Finance & E-Commerce Segment was not part of the Group's business until the end of April
2014 (but had previously been operated by the larger group of which the Company was a part until 2007).
On 30 April 2014, the Group acquired the business through the purchase of all outstanding loan
receivables and other assets from the Consortio Fashion Group and other entities which are under joint
control of the same ultimate shareholders which also control the TF Bank Group. As a result, the Group's
previous financial statements for the years 2012 and 2013 did not include results of operations for the
Sales Finance & E-Commerce Segment. In 2014, only the results of operations starting in May 2014 are
included in the Sales Finance & E-Commerce Segment. In the LTM Period ended 30 June 2015 (which
includes a true full year of financial operations) the total operating income amounted to €15.4 million and
operating profit amounted to €1.9 million in the Sales Finance & E-Commerce Segment.

In March 2015, the joint venture Avarda with Intrum Justitia started its initial operations which
principally focused on signing up merchants to its white label invoice solution product offering. As at 30
June 2015, Avarda had put agreements in place with ten merchants and as at the date of this prospectus
one additional merchant had signed an agreement with Avarda. The Group's directly signed four
merchants had an annual turnover of approximately €120 million in 2014 based on information available
to the Group. At the end of 31 December 2014, the Group had €38.1 million in loans to the public
outstanding through these four merchants and achieved a total net interest income of €8.6 million in 2014
(for the eight months from 1 May 2014 to 31 December 2014). As a comparison, the ten merchants which
Avarda has signed as at 30 June 2015 have a combined annual turnover of approximately €620 million in
the Nordics relevant for Avarda based on information available to the Group. Avarda primarily targets
large merchants that offer significant turnover rates. Operations in Avarda are still being started up with a
target of running full operations for its merchants in the fourth quarter of 2015. As a result, the Group's
results of operations were impacted by start-up costs for Avarda in the six-month period ended 30 June
2015.
Geographic Expansion within Europe

The Group is geographically diversified and has operations in Sweden, Finland, Norway, Denmark,
Estonia, Latvia and Poland. In June 2015, the Group registered with the SFSA to passport its banking
license into the Czech Republic and Slovakia where operations are currently starting up. A key driver for
the Group's increase in loan applications and also its total operating income in the last several years was
its expansion into other markets, in particular Poland in 2013. In Poland the Group received 116,000 new
loan applications in 2014 in the Direct Consumer Business Segment (34% of the total 337,000 loan
applications in 2014) compared to only 7,000 new loan applications in 2013. This growth momentum
continued with 137,000 new loan applications in the LTM Period ended 30 June 2015. In the past,
approval rates have been low in Poland (between 5% and 13% on a monthly basis in the period between
July 2014 and June 2015), but the Group's management expects to increase these rates following the

buildup of enough user profiles for scoring in the database. Similarly, in 2015, the Group has and expects
to further grow with its existing and new merchants in its Sales Finance & E-Commerce Segment as part
of its goal to create a pan-European online and mobile bank.

The following table provides an overview of the development of the geographic distribution of loans to
the public of the Group for both the Group's segments (Sales Finance & E-Commerce Segment included
only from May 2014):
Loan Application Trends and Approval Rates in the Direct Consumer Business Segmen

key_factor_affecting_results: Loan Application Trends and Approval Rates in the Direct Consumer Business Segment

blobs.text:
The larger of the Group's two segments is the Direct Consumer Business Segment which accounted for
69.6% of the total operating income in the LTM Period ended 30 June 2015. The Group maintained its
total operating income in this segment at a relatively stable level at €34.0 million in 2012, €36.4 million
in 2013 and €34.9 million in 2014 and €35.2 million in the LTM Period ended 30 June 2015, while
keeping a high operating profit margin: 32.7% or €11.1 million in 2012, 34.9% or €12.7 million in 2013,
34.6% or €12.0 million in 2014 and 37.1% or €13.1 million in the LTM Period ended 30 June 2015. This
development was principally the result of the following factors:

   The Group concentrated on geographically expanding the Group's Direct Consumer Business
    Segment since 2013 as part of its drive to create a pan-European online and mobile bank. As a
    result, it was able to increase the loan applications received per year, which grew from 179,000
    applications in 2012 to 227,000 applications in 2013 and 337,000 applications in 2014 and
    372,000 applications in the LTM Period ended 30 June 2015. The Group's management decided
    to maintain profitability throughout the geographic expansion by carefully managing the level of
    non-performing loans through low approval rates. The approval rate for loan applications in
    Poland was approximately 10% in 2014, while the Group's average approval rate in its other
    markets was much higher up to 65% in 2014. This is part of the Group's strategy to first build up
    a sufficient number of data points for scoring in local markets before increasing approval rates
    and thus increasing the overall loan portfolio.

   In Sweden, which is a mature market for consumer finance, the Group is subject to significant
    competitive pressure which reduced the number of loans granted to the public between 2012 and
    2014. In Finland, a branch was founded in January 2014 in order to manage larger loan volume
    growth. In Estonia, a subsidiary was started in August 2014. In January 2015, a branch in Poland
    was established with local Polish employees in Gdansk providing the Group with knowledge and
    local experience in the Polish market. This decentralization strategy has increased the overall
    headcount and costs to the Group.
Cross-Selling from Direct Consumer Business Segment to Sales Finance & E-Commerce Segment

key_factor_affecting_results: Cross-Selling from Direct Consumer Business Segment to Sales Finance & E-Commerce Segment

blobs.text:
The Group cross-sells its unsecured loans and is starting to sell its credit cards to customers in its Sales
Finance & E-Commerce Segment. As at 30 June 2015, of the Group's 1.0 million sales finance customer
base (customers who have made a purchase with a merchant and received a loan from the Group since 1
January 2012), about 2.5% have also received an unsecured loan in the past. This percentage varies
widely among the Group's existing markets with 2% in Sweden, 5% in Finland and 12% in Estonia.
Product Diversification through Partnerships and the Acquisition of BB Finans

key_factor_affecting_results: Product Diversification through Partnerships and the Acquisition of BB Finans

blobs.text:
In July 2015, the Group completed the acquisition of the Norwegian company BB Finans for NOK 69.6
million (approximately €7.9 million as at 30 June 2015). With this acquisition, the Group acquired the
ability to issue credit cards, which the Group will offer in both its segments. As at 30 June 2015, the
Group had 1.1 million active customers, which the Group believes offers a significant potential in the
number of credit cards BB Finans can issue to customers through TF Bank Group. As at 30 June 2015,
BB Finans had approximately 5,000 credit cards outstanding with a loan balance of NOK 22.7 million
(approximately €2.5 million as at 30 June 2015) and NOK 116.4 million (approximately €13 million as at
30 June 2015) in approximately 3,000 unsecured loans. BB Finans received 91,000 loan applications in
2014 and had to reject more than 90% of these loan applications because it lacked the resources and funds
to increase the overall loan portfolio. Between 65% and 70% of BB Finans' outstanding credit cards have
been activated as at 30 June 2015. The Group believes there are growth opportunities through BB Finans
due to economies of scale, providing BB Finans with access to cheaper and more financing and
introducing a better IT platform, primarily regarding the credit origination processes.

The Group has partnered with SafeCharge Card Services which is developing an online digital wallet and
mobile application which customers can access online or download to their smart phones and use similar
to a virtual credit card. The Group has agreed to provide the unsecured credit function for the application
which is targeted to be launched in the fourth quarter of 2015 or the first quarter of 2016. The Group has
also, through BB Finans, partnered with Odin Kapital to provide unsecured loans through credit cards to
Norwegian dental patients.

Other envisioned partnerships and product expansions include "brick-and-mortar" payment terminal
solutions that the Group is currently discussing with a partner in the Baltics and payment solutions for an
auction side in the Baltics. These partnerships have not yet been launched.
Price Pressure from Competition and Regulatory Changes

key_factor_affecting_results: Price Pressure from Competition and Regulatory Changes

blobs.text:
The online banking market, for both direct consumer and sales finance products, is highly competitive.
Competition has significantly impacted the margins and profitability of companies operating in the
mature market segments of the consumer credit market in Europe. Many competing banks or other
companies offer consumer finance products at a lower cost for the consumer, particularly on larger
amounts, although these products may differ from those offered by the Group. Additionally, price
pressure also exists due to regulatory measures, in particular as a result of consumer protection initiatives
by governments or other regulatory authorities.

Recently, the regulative environment has tightened in many of the European markets, especially those
which are mature and have historically had low regulatory thresholds of market entry (for more
information on the regulatory environment, see "Regulation"). Increased regulation aimed at the payday
or SMS loan sector may, to an extent, help the Group distinguish itself from these unsecured loan
providers and has been the case for example in Finland, which introduced rate caps in 2013 that
ultimately led to an increase in the Group's business. Further, such initiatives are being discussed in other
markets in which the Group operates. While the Group believes these regulatory pressures will help
consolidate the market and eliminate competition from companies currently offering payday or SMS
loans, some regulatory changes could also affect the Group and its product offerings. Compliance with
regulatory requirements has impacted the Group's operating income in the past.
Payment Behavior, the Group's Risk Management and Seasonality

key_factor_affecting_results: Payment Behavior, the Group's Risk Management and Seasonality

blobs.text:
In all countries in which the Group operates, the emergence of loan brokers has meant that the number of
loan applications has increased in recent years, because the Group's unsecured loan products now reach a
wider audience. The Group decided in the past, however, to maintain its chosen level of risk which has
meant that the number of applications has grown disproportionately to the number of approvals. However,
the Group still benefits from increases in applications because application data is an important source of
"big data" and is used in refining the internal score card for customer applicants. Online direct sales to
new customers, direct marketing activities to existing customers, the establishment of new business
segments, cross-selling activities between business segments and continued geographical expansion are
aimed at reducing the risk of disproportionate increases in operational activities in relation to disbursal
rates or approved online purchases.

The number of applications in Poland is already the largest number of all the Group's existing markets.
Approval rates in Poland are, as a result of risk management decisions, lower than in the other markets as
the Group has been integrating with new sales channels and gathering and analyzing data from them in
order to refine its credit scoring model (TF Score). As the database grows and the distribution networks
become more established, the number of applications is expected to continue to grow and approval rates
are anticipated to rise.

There is a certain monthly variation due to calendar effects and tax returns from governments to private
individuals. Seasonality in loan losses during a quarter or a half-year period is, however, limited due to
such effects generally offsetting themselves over a quarter or a half-year period.

Net interest income

Net interest income consists of the net sum of interest income and interest expense. The following table
shows details of the composition of interest income and interest expense:

Interest income consists of interest income on loans to the public in both the Group's segment and invoice
fees and is the principal income source for the Group. Invoice fees are approximately €2-3 per invoice.

Interest expense relates to interest expense paid to credit institutions, mainly for drawings and fees on the
Group's credit facility, interest expense paid to the public on saving accounts and certain other financial
expenses.
Net fee and commission income

Net fee and commission income consists of fee and commission income and fee and commission
expenses. The following table shows details of fee and commission income and fee and commission
expenses:

Fee and commission income principally includes insurance premiums (payment protection insurance) and
reminder fees. Reminder fees are approximately €5-6.

Payment protection insurance relates to insurance which the Group offers customers to cover loan
repayments in case of for example unemployment. In general, a customer is eligible to apply for
insurance if they are over 18, full-time employed for at least the last six months and not subject to a
redundancy notice. The payment protection insurance covers the customers' loan payments if they
become incapacitated or unemployed. It also covers death or hospitalization if the customer is over 64.
Fee and commission expenses relate to insurance commission expenses.

Income tax expense

The current legal structure of the Group is principally exposed to the corporate tax rate in Sweden, which
is 22%. The branches in Finland and Poland pay corporate tax in the respective countries, but due to tax
legislation these payments are settled in Sweden and the exposure is, as a result, also 22%, although
different tax rates apply in Finland and Poland. Operations in other countries, such as Denmark, Estonia
and Latvia, are executed within TF Bank AB and thus the Swedish tax rate 22% is also applicable. There
are, however, three companies in the current legal structure of the Group which are exposed to foreign
corporate tax rates: BB Finans ASA (including its subsidiaries), Avarda OY and TFB Service OÜ. The
current Norwegian corporate tax rate for BB Finans is 27%, the current Finnish corporate tax rate for
Avarda OY is 20% and the current Estonian tax rate for TFB Service OÜ is 0% although there is a tax
rate of 20% at the time of distribution of profits to shareholders.
Minority interests

The Group and Intrum Justitia partnered on a joint venture, Avarda AB. Avarda started initial operations
in March of 2015. As a result, the income statement and balance sheet of the Company includes a line
"minority interest". In the first half of 2015, start up costs for Avarda resulted in a loss attributable to
Intrum Justitia. Full operations are expected for the fourth quarter of 2015.

was attributed to Intrum Justitia's minority interest in Avarda's results of operations in the first six months

Liquidity is monitored on a daily basis within the Group. The Group uses treasury bills and also deposits
excess cash with various highly rated banks in the Nordics. The Group has an internal policy that 30% of
deposits from the public should be readily available in cash and cash equivalents and/or credit facilities.

   Capital Ratio Pillar 1 as defined as the Swedish capital ratio pillar 1 set out by Swedish law

   Interest Coverage Ratio as defined as EBT plus interest cost divided by interest cost needs to be
    higher than 2.5; and

   Net Stable Funding Ratio as set out in the relevant Swedish and international requirements needs
    to equal or exceed 100%(1).

MARKET INFORMATION
Introduction

The Group operates as an online bank in the direct consumer finance and sales finance & e-commerce
markets. Within the direct consumer finance business, the Group offers loan amounts of generally up to
€4,000 (or up to €6,000 for joint applicants, with the average being approximately €2,000) to consumers
directly through personal loans or credit cards. In the Sales Finance & E-Commerce Segment the Group
works with online or point of sale merchants and provides merchant-tailored invoice solutions for their
customers to facilitate the purchase of goods via invoice or installment payment systems. The Group also
offers savings accounts to consumers in Sweden and Finland, which are protected under the Swedish
Deposit Protection Program. Companies operating within the Group's two market segments have created
a variety of products in response to market demand that reflect the needs of customers for alternative
financing solutions. Customer needs and preferences and affiliate merchant cooperation are the most
important market drivers within these respective business segments.

The Group also differentiates its business segments by geographic operation. In certain geographic
regions, customer profiles and behavior shape the characteristics of the products offered by the Group.
Market demand for Group products also varies by region.
The Direct Consumer Business Market

In the direct consumer business market, the Group provides unsecured personal loans, credit cards and
deposits to consumers through its fully-automated proprietary IT platform. The overwhelming majority of
customers today apply for loans online, in many cases using a mobile device or, alternatively, although
rarely utilized, via telephone or paper application submitted to the Group's customer service
representatives. The adoption of online and mobile banking has in recent years changed the way
customers borrow money. This development is part of the rapid growth of the Internet and online services
which began in the late 1990s and further developed as point-of-sale finance companies and short-term
credit lenders entered the market during and as a result of the financial crisis in 2008 and 2009, when
several large, traditional banking institutions were forced to reduce the amount of credit available to
consumers. In the view of the Company's management, the widespread acceptance of online banking
solutions and the convenience of applying for a loan online is also an important factor for consumers and
contributor for this growth.

Through its Direct Consumer Business Segment, the Group currently offers unsecured loans and financial
products directly to consumers in Sweden, Norway, Finland, Estonia and Poland. The Group plans to
begin operations in the Czech Republic and Slovakia in the near future and is analyzing a market entry in
the UK, the Netherlands, Austria, Germany, Latvia and Lithuania. The Group takes deposits in Sweden
and Finland only. The Group recently started its credit card business in Norway through the acquisition of
Norwegian finance company BB Finans and intends to extend its credit card product offerings in all of the
direct consumers markets in which it currently operates.

Northern Europe – Sweden, Finland and Norway

Consumer Credit Market

Consumer credit in the Group's key Northern European markets increased steadily over the last several
years. The following table shows the outstanding consumer credit for the years ended 31 December 2010
until 31 December 2014 (consumer credit encompasses loans granted primarily for purposes of personal
consumption of goods and services, generally without collateral):

In Northern Europe, increasing regulation in the direct consumer finance market has recently affected the
market. For example, new regulations introduced in 2012 regarding extra charges applied to consumers
paying for purchases by credit card continue to have a negative impact on consumer lending in Denmark
by limiting growth rates in card lending. Similarly, 2014 saw the introduction of greater surveillance,
monitoring and control of the granting of SMS loans in Sweden. SMS loans are small loans obtained via
an SMS text message request that are characterized by proportionally high interest rates and fees, which
usually must be repaid within 30 days. Despite these changes, the consumer credit markets in Northern
Europe have developed favorably for the Group.
Deposits

The Group takes deposits from customers in Sweden in SEK and in Finland in euro. In both countries,
recent years have shown strong growth in the overall amounts of deposits. The following table provides

All deposits the Group accepts are guaranteed by the Swedish Deposit Protection Program which
guarantees deposits up to an equivalent of €100,000. The limit was raised to €100,000 at the end of 2010
as a result of the financial crisis in 2008 and 2009. This resulted in an increased deposit volume that was
transferred from larger universal banks to other deposit institutions, including smaller banks such as the
Group, as customers started to seek opportunities for more attractive terms for their deposits.
Credit Cards

With the acquisition of the Norwegian financial institution BB Finans in July 2015, the Group also gained
access to technology and licenses to offer credit cards to consumers. The credit card industry is currently
undergoing changes worldwide and has recently been the subject of planned EU legislation to set fee caps
and implement other restrictions that afford more protections for consumers and retailers that utilize
credit card products and services.

In Northern Europe, where the Group aims to initially roll out its credit card offering, credit card
receivables have increased strongly over the last several years. As at 31 December 2014, 19.7 million
debit and credit cards were in issue in Sweden, of which approximately 16.4 million were issued by banks
and 3.3 million by other licensed credit card issuers. Credit card receivables increased from SEK 36.9
billion as at 31 December 2010 to SEK 42.4 billion as at 31 December 2014. Similarly to Sweden,
Norway has an established credit card history and the Group considers it a good base to adopt established
routines and develop integrated IT systems.
Baltic Countries – Estonia

In the Direct Consumer Business Segment, the Group currently only operates in Estonia within the Baltic
region. While the number of customers and revenues compared to the Group's activities in Northern
Europe is smaller, the Group's management believes that Estonia is a solid market. Due to generally good
payment behavior, Estonia currently has the highest approval rates for unsecured loans in the Group.
Central and Eastern Europe – Poland, Czech Republic and Slovakia

The Group currently operates in Poland and plans to soon begin its operations in the Czech Republic and
Slovakia in the Central and Eastern European region. Consumer spending in Poland is expected to
increase in the future due to increasingly favorable economic conditions, which is expected to lead to an
increase in consumer lending. Favorable legislation in 2013 has led to an increase in the willingness of
banks to issue cash and card loans combined with increasing regulations to restrict the activity of non-
bank lenders. (Source: Euromonitor International: Consumer Lending in Sweden, January 2015)

The Czech Republic saw strong growth in terms of both gross lending and outstanding balance in 2014,
with card lending demonstrating the most progressive growth. The outlook for consumer lending remains
very positive. (Source: Euromonitor International: Consumer Lending in the Czech Republic, January
2015). The market in Slovakia is similarly structured to the Czech Republic.
The Sales Finance & E-Commerce Market
E-commerce

In the Sales Finance & E-Commerce market, the Group operates in the Northern European countries of
Sweden, Norway, Finland and Denmark, in the Baltic countries of Estonia and Latvia. The Group is also
currently starting operations in Eastern and Central Europe in Poland, the Czech Republic and Slovakia
and is analyzing a market entry in the UK, the Netherlands, Austria, Germany and Lithuania.

Current markets
Currently starting operations
New markets being analyzed

The e-commerce sales finance market allows customers to purchase goods from merchants with
intermediaries, such as the TF Bank Group, assuming the immediate payment obligation to the merchant.
As a result, the customer receives purchased goods from the merchant and the merchant receives payment
from the intermediary without further delay. The customer payment obligations are transferred from the
merchant to the sales finance provider on alternate payment terms such as installments, allowing the
provider to collect fees and interest in exchange for immediate satisfaction of the customer debt to the
merchant. With the growth of online shopping, the sales finance & e-commerce market has expanded
rapidly in recent years. In Central Europe for example, online sales grew on average by 20% from 2010 to
2014. (Source: Ecommerce Europe, June 2014) and in the Nordic region, upper single-digit to double-
digit annual growth rates are expected by market analysts for the years 2015 to 2017 (Source: PostNord,
E-commerce in the Nordics, 2015). Overall, e-commerce revenues for goods and services in Europe
totaled approximately €93 billion in 2014 (Source: Ecommerce Europe, October 2014), demonstrating the
growing prevalence of online sales and e-commerce finance products.

The European online sales market is currently dominated by the UK, Germany and France. However, a
growing number of Nordic residents are shopping online, with approximately 12.4 million people in the
region completing online purchases during each quarter of 2014, purchasing a total of approximately
€15.4 billion worth of goods (Source: PostNord, E-commerce in the Nordics, 2015). The following
overview of predicted online retail sales growth demonstrates the rapid growth across Europe including in
two of the Group's target markets, Poland and Sweden (Source: Centre for Retail Research, Online
Retailing: Britain, Europe, US and Canada, January 2015):

As a general trend, online consumers in Europe are expected to make more online transactions in 2015
than 2014, with an average 17.8 online transaction per consumer expected in 2015 compared to 15.8 in
2014. The average online shopper in Europe is also expected to spend approximately €970 in 2015, an
increase from €874 per shopper in 2014. (Source: Centre for Retail Research, Online Retailing: Britain,
Europe, US and Canada, January 2015)
Point of Sale

The Group's point of sale product (TFB Store) was successfully launched in 2015 and enables customers
to choose an invoice or installment option when shopping in physical "brick and mortar" locations,
similar to sales finance options offered by the Group to online consumers. The Group is also currently in
negotiations with a partner in the Baltics to provide a point of sale credit solution for payment terminals
in the Baltics.

The Group's management believes that due to the lower interchange fees for merchants, both independent
and chain retailers are increasingly eager to install point of sale terminals in their outlets. Additionally,
declining interchange fees, the rising popularity of contactless cards and the introduction of mobile
payments will likely further decrease cash payments in the future.
Geographic Differences in Target Countries

The Group's sales finance business in the Northern European countries primarily focuses on products
offered to end consumers through e-commerce merchants and, recently, also through similar point of sale
products offered in physical stores. E-commerce is an accepted and growing feature of everyday life in
Nordic countries, although the level of online shopping varies by country. For example, 27% of people in
Sweden shop online at least once a month, versus 19% in Finland, 36% in Norway and 37% in Denmark.

The preferred method of payment for online purchases in Sweden, Denmark, Norway and Finland is by
debit or credit card, with invoice payment being the second most preferred payment method (and nearly
as preferred as debit or credit cards in Sweden and Finland). Other, less popular forms of online payment
include direct bank transfers, payment through other processers, such as PayPal, Inc., or other alternative
payment methods.

Internet penetration and the ratio of the population with Internet access compared to those who purchased
products online in 2014 comprises a large percentage of the total population in the Nordics (Source:

Similarly, Internet penetration in Baltic countries continues to grow, with corresponding strong
development in online shopping as well as growth in mobile shopping. In Central and Eastern Europe, the
Group intends to begin offering sales finance products to merchants in Poland, the Czech Republic and
Slovakia in the near future. Payment preferences for online shopping in Poland include bank transfers and
other instant online payment methods in addition to invoice payments. The Company believes there are

attractive growth opportunities in Central and Eastern Europe and the Baltics, as the current Internet

Competition

The EU consumer credit market, the sales finance & e-commerce market and the consumer credit card
markets are all highly fragmented with many new suppliers entering the direct consumer financing
business as well as the e-commerce sales finance business. Competition has increased steadily as
alternative finance products have become established as reliable sources of consumer financing.

In the direct consumer market in Northern Europe, a number of companies currently offer unsecured
personal loans. Competitors differ in terms of country and customer profile. The Swedish universal banks
are active in certain segments and, in certain segments, competitors mainly consist of other banks and
credit companies, such as Marginalen Bank AB, Nordax Bank AB, Resurs Bank AB and Santander
Consumer Finance Oy. In recent years, the distribution channel for personal loans has developed and
independent, Internet-based loan intermediaries, such as Lendo AS and Freedom Finance Limited, have
taken a larger share of the market and thereby also increased transparency between players and
contributed to increased options for customers. In Poland, competitors in the personal loans markets are
Meritum Bank ICB S.A., Allior Bank S.A. and Bank BPH S.A. In Estonia, the Group's management
believes its main competitors are Swedbank AB, Skandinaviska Enskilda Banken AB and Big Bank AS.

In the sales finance & e-commerce market, there are a number of players delivering invoice and
installment solutions in Northern Europe. Certain competitors focus primarily e-commerce, including
Klarna AB, the current market leader, as well as other smaller competitors such as Arvato Finance AB,
Collector AB and Svea Ekonomi AB. In recent years, a number of new players have begun to focus on
payment solutions in e-commerce and customers have increasingly demanded a complete solution
whereby various payment methods are accepted and handled by a single supplier.

The Swedish and Norwegian credit card market include a large number of banks and credit companies
that issue cards, in the form of either debit and/or credit cards. The largest four Swedish banks are the
largest issuers of debit and credit cards in the Swedish market. In addition, EnterCard Sverige AB, Resurs
Bank AB and IKANO Bank AB are major credit card issuers.

The Swedish and Finnish deposit market includes a large number of banks, credit institutions and deposit
institutions offering deposit accounts, either with or without the Deposit Protection Program. The larger
banks hold most of the deposit volumes, however, the Group uses changes to its interest rate to attract
deposits as required for financing of its lending business.

In Poland, TF Bank Group competes with banks such as Meritum, Allior, Bank BPH, BZ WBK or
Santander Consumer Bank in the personal loan market and with Credit Agricole (Lukas Finanse),
Santander Consumer Bank, mBank, Alior Bank or Sygma Bank in the sales finance & e-commerce
market and with Citi Handlowy, BZ WBK, Alior Bank, Credit Agricole, Raiffeisen Polbank or Santander
Consumer Bank in the credit card market.

In Estonia, the Group competes with Swedbank, SEB, Nordea, Danske, LHV and Bigbank in the personal
loan market, with Koduliising, Bigbank and LHV in the sales finance & e-commerce business and with
Swedbank, SEB, LHV, Nordea and Danske Bank in the credit card market.

Lastly, the Group may be competing with various other companies in the future, such as Apple Inc. which
is currently aiming to expand its "Apple Pay" product and with Google Inc.'s "Google Wallet" product or
with PayPal Inc. which offers payment services.
Market Trends

The Company believes there are a number of market trends that are currently driving changes in the
financial services sector and most importantly in the unsecured consumer and e-commerce sales financing
sector:

   Financial Technology products and real-time scoring using a "big data" approach: The Group
    has built up an IT and automatic scoring system based on a "big data" approach that it can use for
    a variety of financial products. TF Bank's management believes that this "plug and play"
    approach for its IT system into various products, from online virtual credit cards to physical store
    point of sale system, cashless payments and various other system where retail customers' either
    require credit or a payment solution, is in line with the market trend towards providing niche
    online banking services that customers are increasingly demanding.

   Online/Mobile banking: In recent years, major changes have taken place in European banking
    and finance markets and the Company believes this will continue. The need for physical bank
    branches and traditional banking operations is decreasing. In today's society, bank customers
    increasingly want to be able to save, borrow and pay online or via mobile devices. This requires
    considerable product development and efficiency enhancement among the banking and financial
    market players.

   Growth in e-commerce: The proportion of consumers having made purchases using their phone
    or tablet increased strongly in the last several years in the markets in which the Group operates.
    As a result, the need for payment solutions is also increasing. Internet-focused invoice and
    installment players have experienced high growth in recent years and this trend is expected to
    continue.

   Changed credit behavior with credit needs in new sectors: The consumer credit market has
    undergone considerable development in recent years and currently represents an increasing part
    of people's day-to-day finances. Through the Internet the availability of consumer credit has
    increased and been simplified. This has also entailed the need for consumer credit shifting to new
    sectors, such as in the travel sector where credit penetration was previously low. The Company
    believes this will benefit through increased market volumes.

   The Swedish Financial Supervisory Authority has tightened capital requirements: The current
    total capital requirement is 10.5% including a capital conservation buffer of 2.5%. From
    September 2015 onwards the SFSA will tighten the requirement by introducing a countercyclical
    requirement of 1%, which is intended to be increased to 1.5% in June 2016. The principal aim of
    the increased requirements is to reduce the systemic risks in the banking system and the focus has
    primarily been on the larger, systemically important banks. Increased capital requirements and
    higher risk weights have limited the lending capacity of the larger banks, while providing
    business and growth opportunities for specialized lenders such as the Group.
BUSINESS
Introduction

The TF Bank Group is an online bank which offers consumer finance products directly to retail customers
and offers e-commerce solutions to merchants in seven countries in Northern Europe, the Baltics and
Central and Eastern Europe. As at 30 June 2015, the Group had a total of 1.1 million active customers in
its two segments and a combined 2.2 million of user profiles for scoring in its database. The Group was
granted a banking license from the Swedish regulator SFSA in 2012, allowing the Group to offer banking
services in the entire European Economic Area. The Group's banking services include unsecured loans,
credit cards and savings accounts for retail customers which are insured by the Swedish Deposit
Protection Program. The Group uses various distribution channels to market its products, including
through partnerships and physical payment terminals.
