blobs.text:
The Company, as an incorporated entity, started its Direct Consumer Business in 1987, offering mail
order customers the opportunity to borrow money for purposes other than catalogue purchases. In the
mid-2000s to late 2000s, the Company under new management and ownership began refocusing its
business towards online banking products. Following the market developments in the consumer finance
industry and as a result of the increasing importance of the Internet and smart phones, the Group
refocused its business into pan-European online and mobile banking and entered the e-commerce
financing sector.

In 1998, the TF Bank Group made the decision to geographically expand its operations to Finland and in
2002, to Norway and the Baltics. In 2013, the Group launched operations in Poland and in 2014,
expanded its online sales to Denmark. The Group is currently in the process of launching its operations in
the Czech Republic and Slovakia and is analyzing the possibility of a market entry in Austria, Germany
and the UK. Due to this geographic expansion, the TF Bank Group now operates in markets with a total
population of 85 million.

The TF Bank Group is structured into two distinct segments which both utilize the Group's IT system and
big data scoring models, but on different customer bases:

Direct Consumer Business Segment: In the Direct Consumer Business Segment, the Group
principally offers unsecured loans to consumers up to €4,000 for individual applicants and up to
€6,000 for joint loan applicants with a length of up to five years for personal usage (such as home
improvements, holiday travel or the purchase of goods). In the LTM Period ended 30 June 2015,
the Direct Consumer Business Segment contributed 69.6% or €35.2 million to the Group's
overall operating income. As at 30 June 2015, the Group had €139.1 million in unsecured loans
outstanding in this segment with an average loan value per customer of €2,055 in the LTM
Period and an average length per loan, depending on the country of 16 to 19 months. With the
acquisition of Norwegian finance company BB Finans, the Group also gained the ability to offer
credit cards to consumers and is in the process of initiating an expansion of this product to all its
target countries.

Sales Finance & E-Commerce Segment: In the Sales Finance & E-Commerce Segment, the
Group offers merchant-tailored invoice solutions (so-called "white label" solutions) and takes
credit risk for merchants by providing loan financing for end customers. In the LTM Period
ended 30 June 2015, the Sales Finance & E-Commerce Segment contributed 30.4% or €15.4
million to the Group's overall operating income. As at 30 June 2015, the Group had €38.5 million
in loans outstanding to end customers. As at 30 June 2015, the average loan amount per approved
loan was €122 and the average length per loan, depending on the country, of nine to eleven
months. The Sales Finance & E-Commerce Segment had total active customer base of 1,033,000
customers who received loans since 1 January 2012 as of 30 June 2015 of which more 830,000 or
over 80% had an open balance outstanding in the LTM Period ended 30 June 2015.

As part of the Group's Fintech strategy, the Group has started various partnerships to increase its total
active end customer base. In the Sales Finance & E-Commerce Segment, it formed a joint venture,
Avarda, with Intrum Justitia, one of the leading credit management services companies in Europe. Intrum
Justitia has approximately 3,800 employees and is present in 20 European countries. Intrum Justitia's
shares are listed on the NASDAQ OMX Nordic large cap-segment list of companies. Avarda is focused
on Northern Europe (Sweden, Finland, Norway and Denmark) and offers flexible online payment

solutions for e-commerce merchants including white label invoice solutions which allow merchants to
utilize the Group's services and offer payment products to their consumers under their own brand and
tailored to their own needs. In the Direct Consumer Business Segment, the Group recently partnered with
SafeCharge Card Services to provide credit financings to Nordic retail customers as part of SafeCharge
Card Service's "digital wallet" mobile application solution utilizing the MasterCard ecosystem. The
SafeCharge Group is a global provider of payments services, technologies and risk management solutions
for online and mobile businesses and is listed on the London Stock Exchange. The Group, through BB
Finans, also partnered with Odin Kapital to offer a point-of-sale online dental payment service
(DentaPay) in Norway. Other partnerships, which the Group is currently negotiating in or in the process
of preparing to launch, are an e-commerce financing solution for an online auction site in the Baltics and
credit applications through physical card payment terminals in the Baltics.
History

The Company was incorporated in Sweden in 1987 for the purpose of offering consumer finance
solutions to customers ordering goods from mail order catalogues. Over time, the Group has grown in
terms of both revenue and geographic presence. Today, the Group offers consumer banking services
through a fully-automated proprietary IT platform designed for scalability and adaptation to different
digital banking solutions.
The following is a description of the major milestones in the TF Bank Group's history.

   The core of the Group's business was created in the 1980s under the name Aktiebolaget Time
    Finans and operated during the 1990s and 2000s primarily under the trade names of Time Finans
    and Haléns Finance. Until the late 1990s, the Group remained focused on its Swedish home
    market and on mail order catalogue financing.

   As part of its strategy to diversify its business geographically, the Group expanded its operations
    into Finland (1998), Estonia (2002) and Norway (2003).

   In 2007, the Group, under new ownership, accelerated its focus on online and mobile lending as
    well as e-commerce finance solutions. In 2008, the Company received a new management and
    also changed its name to Time Finans AB.

   In 2012, the Company further changed its name to "TF Bank AB" and was granted a banking
    license from the SFSA.

   In 2013 and 2014, the Group expanded operations into Poland and acquired the business and
    assets from a related and long-time co-operation partner in the mail order business. The Group
    also used its cross border license to start activities in Latvia and Denmark.

   In 2014, the Group established a branch in Finland, allowing it to accept deposits in euro.

   At the end of 2014, the Group expanded its online sales financing operations by establishing
    Avarda, its joint venture with Intrum Justitia which launched its initial operations in March 2015.

   In 2015, the Group established a branch in Poland.

   In July 2015, the Group acquired the Norwegian financial institute BB Finans, a consumer loan
    specialist company based in Norway through which the Group acquired technology and licenses
    to issue credit cards, gaining access to the Norwegian consumer finance market, further credit
    card technology and licenses.
Strengths

The Company management believes that the following are the key strengths that allowed the Group to
reach its current size and operational efficiency:

The Group operates a consistently profitable consumer finance and Fintech business in the fast
growing European consumer finance and e-commerce markets

competitive_strength: The Group operates a consistently profitable consumer finance and Fintech business in the fastgrowing European consumer finance and e-commerce markets

blobs.text:
The Group operates in the unsecured consumer loan market and in the sales finance and e-commerce
market. Both markets, especially the e-commerce market, have shown strong growth in recent years and
the Group believes the markets in which it operates will develop favorably in the future. The Group has
maintained consistent profitability in recent years, with net profit margins (net profit for the period
attributable to shareholders of the Company divided by interest income for the period) of 20.8% in 2012,
25.2% in 2013, 23.6% in 2014 and 23.4% in the LTM Period ended 30 June 2015. While competition in
both markets is fierce, the TF Bank Group believes that its merchant background, long history, well-
developed scoring system and focus on online and retail customer activities combined with a lean
company structure with a focus on IT solutions resulting in only 77 employees as at 30 June 2015
(including nine BB Finans employees included in the Group from July 2015) provides it with a significant
competitive advantage compared to other companies in these markets.

The Group has geographically diversified in recent years. While it originally only operated in Sweden, it
has expanded to all Nordic countries as well as to the Baltics and Poland. Most recently, the Group also
prepared to launch operations in the Czech Republic and Slovakia. The Group's current market presence
provides access to a potential base of approximately 85 million customers in Northern Europe, the Baltics
and Poland. The Group believes that this diversified geographical footprint and the experience gained
operating in several countries, are a significant advantage over local competitors which only operate in
one market or in a limited number of markets.

The Group has substantial growth potential through its various partnerships in both of its business
segments

competitive_strength: The Group has substantial growth potential through its various partnerships in both of its businesssegments

blobs.text:
In 2014, the Group's management made the strategic decision to utilize its automated IT scoring and loan
application processing system within partnering models as part of its goal to grow its end customer base
with a multi-pronged approach.

In the Sales Finance & E-commerce Segment, the Group partnered with Intrum Justitia, a leading
European credit management and financial services provider with approximately 3,800 employees
operating in 20 countries and with revenues of SEK 5.2 billion as at 31 December 2014. The resulting
joint venture, Avarda, was set up in early 2015 and began operations and partnership efforts with
merchants in March 2015. As at 30 June 2015, Avarda has established agreements with ten merchants in
the Nordic countries and between 30 June 2015 and the date of this Prospectus one additional merchant.
The Group's management believes that this joint venture will significantly grow its operating income in
the Sales Finance & E-Commerce Segment.

In 2015 the Group teamed up with SafeCharge Card Services, a company which developed an online
digital wallet and mobile application based on the MasterCard ecosystem which provides virtual credit
cards based on an online and mobile application solution. The Group also cooperates with Odin Kapital
through BB Finans to offer a point-of-sale online dental payment service (DentaPay) in Norway. Other
partnerships which are in development include the integration of the Group's installment loan offerings in
physical payment terminals in the Baltics and the integration of a loan offering option for a Baltics
auction website. The Group's management intends to continue to seek cooperation partners with which it
can work on mutually beneficial finance solutions through which the Group can access additional
customers and the cooperation partner can access the Group's IT-based consumer credit banking services
which allows the partner the ability to offer additional credit to its consumers.

While the Group's key partnerships have only recently begun, the Group has already seen significant
initial benefits from the added channels to access end customers. For instance, Avarda, which launched
operations in March 2015, has already signed ten merchant partners as at 30 June 2015, with a combined
annual turnover relevant for Avarda in the Nordics relevant to Avarda of approximately €620 million.

The Group operates a "big data" scoring IT-platform which uses a large set of data points to provide
automatic, real-time, risk-assessed scoring and lending decision making processes

competitive_strength: The Group operates a "big data" scoring IT-platform which uses a large set of data points to provideautomatic, real-time, risk-assessed scoring and lending decision making processes

blobs.text:
The Group operates an IT infrastructure which allows fully-automated, real-time and risk-assessed credit
decisions which are usually made within seconds. This IT platform is highly scalable and is used for all

the Group's current markets. The front-end of applications can be tailored to all required languages and
market specific requirements.

Overall, the Group has over 8,000 data points available which it can use for its scoring system. However,
due to its experience with scoring, the Group only uses a limited selection of these data points to score
customers, which varies between each loan product or purchase approval process. This selection and the
exact scoring models also differ from market to market and are constantly monitored and refined. When
the Group enters a new market, it usually starts with lower than Group average approval rates in order to
build up its database and gain experience with the relevant market specifics, which then help to fine-tune
the scoring and approval process for each specific market.
Highly diversified and granulated credit portfolio of unsecured loans

competitive_strength: Highly diversified and granulated credit portfolio of unsecured loans

blobs.text:
The Group's core business involves taking consumer credit risk. The Group therefore has no corporate
customers. The strategy of the Group instead focuses on many smaller individual credit exposures.
Although these exposures could individually be considered high risk (as they are unsecured), in a large,
risk-assessed, geographically diversified and granulated portfolio, where the average loan book value is
approximately €2000 and the average sales finance debt is less than €200, the actual risk for the Group is
lower. Furthermore, the Group matches the tenure of the loans it offers with the size of the debt (i.e., no
"payday" lending demands for repayment after 30 days or less and at the same time no longer term loans
comprising 10 or 15 years for the amounts offered by the Group).

Additionally, the Group employs a "clean balance sheet" approach (in all markets except Norway and
Estonia). It sells non-performing loans to companies which specialize in the collection of non-performing
loans (in 2014, these non-performing loans were sold after an average of 69 days delinquency). The sale
of these non-performing assets has been a conscious management decision as a part of its responsible
lending practices. Due to its scoring system and conservative approach to lending, with an overall
approval rate of about 20% in 2014 (with variation by country ranging from below 10% to 65%) in the
Direct Consumer Business Segment and a customer base in the Sales Finance & E-Commerce Segment
which generally has low default rates (resulting in an overall approval rate in this segment of 91% in
2014), the Group has been able to keep its overall percentage of non-performing loans at a manageable
rate and has historically been able to choose from several offers of various debt collection companies
when putting a forward flow contract out to tender.
The Group employs an efficient cost and financial structure

competitive_strength: The Group employs an efficient cost and financial structure

blobs.text:
The TF Bank Group's loans are provided at nominal interest rates which are generally comparable to
credit cards and range from 10% to 29% depending on the individual customer and the market in which
the loans are provided. Despite differences in nominal interest rates in the various markets in which the
Group operates, the Group usually has an APR of between 20% and 30% in the Sales Finance & E-
Commerce Segment and between 30% and 33% in the Direct Consumer Business Segment, depending on
the respective market. The Group's main financing for providing loans to customers are through its
deposits. Deposit rates are currently 1.05% in Sweden and 1.60% in Finland. Considering the large
margin between the interest rate the Group charges for its financial products and the deposit interest paid
on customer savings accounts, the Group's management believes that its business model is robust even if
interest rates would increase to levels equal to those before the global financial crisis in 2008. The Group
has in the past comfortably adjusted the amounts of deposits required for its financing needs by increasing
or decreasing the rates of offered deposits. Due to online savings account comparison websites, the Group
can generally attract significant new interest in its savings accounts from new customers if it raises its
interest rates on deposits. Because the group takes deposits in both Sweden and Finland, it is to some
extent able to tailor its requirements for funding in euro and SEK depending on its lending needs.

Next to the Group's low-cost source of financing, due to its Swedish bank license, the Group also
employs a lean operational approach and as at 30 June 2015 (excluding BB Finans which has an
additional nine employees) had only 68 employees (full-time equivalents). As a result, the Group operates
with a high net profit margin of 23.6% in 2014 and 23.4% in the LTM Period ended in 30 June 2015. The
Group believes that its current operations can sustain significant further growth and thus realize
economies of scale.
The Group has an experienced management team

competitive_strength: The Group has an experienced management team

blobs.text:
The TF Bank Group has a highly experienced management team with a combined experience of more
than 50 years in the financial sector. Mattias Carlsson, the current chairman of the board of directors, was
the chief executive officer ("CEO") of TF Bank for six years and has additionally worked at
Skandinaviska Enskilda Banken AB (SEB) in Sweden in credit management in the consumer loan area.
Declan Mac Guinness, the current CEO of TF Bank, was the CEO of a Swedish fund management
company before he started working at TF Bank and also worked at Norway's largest banking group DNB
ASA. Mikael Meomuttel, the Group's CFO has over ten years of experience at financial institutions and
has worked at TF Bank for seven years and also held functions at Consortio Fashion Group, a Swedish e-
commerce company, in the past. Björn Skytt, the Group's CIO has over ten years of experience in
information technology at financial institutions. In addition, the Group has two highly experienced
country managers in its core markets outside of Sweden: Johannes Rintaniemi in Finland who worked at
Citibank, GE Money Bank, Santander Consumer Finance Oy and Ferratum Oyj before he joined TF Bank
and Wojciech Drozd, who is the country manager in Poland and has banking experience from Bank BPH
S.A., GE Money Bank and Dominet Bank S.A. in Poland.
Strategy

The Group's strategy is based on technologically-driven organic growth, geographic expansion, product
portfolio expansion and a vision to establish the TF Bank Group as a leading pan-European online and
mobile bank:
Leveraging Partnerships to increase the Group's end customer base

key_element_strategy: Leveraging Partnerships to increase the Group's end customer base

blobs.text:
The management of the TF Bank Group is focused on growing its end customer base through various
partnerships in both its segments and believes that these partnerships will be the key growth drivers for
the Group's results of operations in the next years:

   The Group's joint venture with Intrum Justitia, Avarda started its initial operations in March of
    2015. The Company owns 51% of Avarda and the remaining 49% is owned by Intrum Justitia.
    Between March 2015 and 30 June 2015, Avarda partnered with ten merchants compared to only
    four merchants that TF Bank is partnering with directly outside of the joint venture. Avarda
    focuses on partnerships with larger merchants, where one partnership can result in access to
    thousands of end-customers. Based on publically available information, the Group estimates that
    the ten merchants Avarda has already signed up have a total annual turnover of €620 million
    relevant to Avarda in the Nordics, compared to a total annual turnover of about €120 million for
    the Group's existing four merchants. Avarda is limited to the Nordic regions, but the Group is
    also offering its invoice solutions outside of the Nordic regions to those merchants signed up by
    Avarda. As a result of the Avarda joint venture, the Group believes that it can significantly grow
    its active customer base in the Sales Finance & E-Commerce Segment.

   In Norway, the Group, through BB Finans, has partnered with Odin Kapital to offer dental
    patients the opportunity to apply for and receive a credit decision before being treated by the
    dentist. This partnership has been launched recently and already signed up dentists with a
    combined annual turnover in excess of NOK 1 billion (approximately €110 million). This type of
    point-of-sale consumer offering is a direct result of the ability to integrate different credit
    origination methods into the Group's IT-platform.

   In its Direct Consumer Business Segment, the Group has partnered with SafeCharge Card
    Services to provide the credit function for SafeCharge Card Service's online digital wallet and
    mobile application. SafeCharge Card Services targets to launch operations for its digital wallet in
    the fourth quarter of 2015 or the first quarter of 2016.

   Other partnerships which are in development include the integration of the Group's installment
    loan offerings in physical payment terminals in the Baltics and the integration of a loan offering
    option for a Baltics auction website.
Cross-selling of its Direct Consumer Business Products to its Sales Finance Customer Base

key_element_strategy: Cross-selling of its Direct Consumer Business Products to its Sales Finance Customer Base

blobs.text:
The Group believes cross-selling its unsecured loan products to the end customer base in its Sales Finance
& E-Commerce Segment will be an important part of its growth in the future. The Group cross-sells its
unsecured loans and is starting to sell its credit cards to customers in its Sales Finance & E-Commerce
Segment. As at 30 June 2015, of the Group's 1.033 million sales finance active customers (customers who
made a purchase with a merchant and received a loan approval from TF Bank Group since 1 January
2012), about 2.5% have also accepted an unsecured loan from the Direct Consumer Business Segment in
the past. This percentage varies widely among the Group's existing markets with 2% in Sweden, 5% in
Finland and 12% in Estonia.

The Group's management aims to increase its sales finance customer base in the future, e.g. through the
Avarda joint venture, which management believes will drive growth in the Direct Consumer Business
Segment through cross-selling, while also lowering marketing costs in the Direct Consumer Business
Segment. The Group principally uses its invoices in its Sales Finance & E-commerce Segment to engage
in cross-selling and also aims to cross-sell its credit cards to its Sales Finance & E-Commerce Segment's
customers.
Invest in Expanding its newly Acquired Credit Card Products and Other Products

key_element_strategy: Invest in Expanding its newly Acquired Credit Card Products and Other Products

blobs.text:
Historically, the Group's products were unsecured loans which it marketed directly to consumers and, to a
lesser extent, e-commerce installment loans marketed via online merchants. Most recently, through the
acquisition of BB Finans, the Group can also offer credit cards and aims to significantly increase the
number of credit cards issued by BB Finans in the future. Despite high number of applications in Norway,
BB Finans was constrained by its small size, its lack of a banking license and thus lack of funding to
grow its business quickly. The Group plans to develop BB Finans, increase approval rates for loan
applications and credit cards using the Group's own financing sources and to also implement the Group's
more sophisticated IT and scoring system at BB Finans.

With regard to the credit card offering of BB Finans, the Group's management intends to initially further
increase the number of credit cards issued in Norway, where credit cards are a popular method of
payment. In addition to the expansion of the credit card offering in Norway, the Group's management
plans to use the credit card license cross-border by first introducing credit cards in Sweden and Finland,
where the majority of the Group's current customer base is located, but also aims to offer credit cards in
Eastern Europe and the Baltics thereafter. In parallel to the Group's focus on the geographical expansion
of a customer base for physical credit cards, the Group also aims to offer virtual credit cards via its
partnership with SafeCharge Card Services.

While the Group's management principally anticipates cross-selling credit cards to its existing loan or
sales finance customers, it also plans to offer credit cards as an alternative offer to applicants who do not
receive approval for a larger unsecured loan amount, but would qualify for lower amounts offered via
credit card.
Geographic Expansion to establish a pan-European online and mobile bank

key_element_strategy: Geographic Expansion to establish a pan-European online and mobile bank

blobs.text:
The TF Bank Group operates in seven European countries. The expansion into Poland (in 2013) only
occurred recently and the Group is currently starting operations in the Czech Republic and Slovakia. As a
result, most of the Group's interest income in 2014 was generated in three core countries, Sweden,
Finland and Estonia. However, the Group's revenue base is diversifying as a result of its recent
geographic expansion, with the percentage of the Group's overall interest income in Poland and the
Baltics increasing in the last years, even though Sweden and Finland remain the Group's core markets
with 81.0% of loans outstanding in these two countries as at 30 June 2015 (not taking into account
approximately €16 million in loans to the public outstanding in Norway through BB Finans) compared to
91.0% of loans outstanding as at 31 December 2012.

The Group's management is currently analyzing the market entry into new European countries. One key
driver of this pan-European expansion is the Group's strong growth in its Sales Finance & E-commerce
Segment. Several of the e-commerce merchants that the Group provides sales finance and invoice
solutions to, have operations in European countries where the Group is not yet present or is looking to
expand its business geographically in the future. The Group's market entry in the Czech Republic and
Slovakia is a direct result of some of the Group's partner-merchants' business operations in these

countries. Consortio Fashion Group, which includes three of the four merchants the Group has directly
signed (Halens, Cellbes & Bubbleroom) asked the Group to start operations in Poland, the Czech
Republic and Slovakia because they had approximately 250,000 customers in Poland, 280,000 customers
in the Czech Republic and approximately 120,000 in Slovakia in 2014. The Sales Finance and E-
Commerce Segment's business is currently being launched in all three of these countries.

The Group is currently analyzing a market entry in the United Kingdom, the Netherlands, Germany,
Austria and Lithuania. The Group's management's long term goal is to establish itself as a pan-European
online and mobile bank.

The Group's EU banking license, which it received in 2012, is the cornerstone for the Group's European
expansion. The Group plans to enter future countries with one consumer finance product, principally its
"white label" e-commerce invoice solution, and then expand in such countries with its other products, if
market conditions are favorable. The Group's management uses its IT infrastructure and scoring system in
all of the countries in which it operates, but tailors the customer scoring system to the relevant market and
availability of external credit data.

In connection with the Group's European expansion, it may diversify its funding sources. The Company's
management currently analysis whether to also take deposits in Poland and whether to increase the share
of deposits it takes in euro in Finland. In addition, the Company's management may in the future also
issue bonds in currencies it requires to support its growth across Europe and to diversify its funding
sources.
Switching from a Dividend-Focused Company to a Growth Company

key_element_strategy: Switching from a Dividend-Focused Company to a Growth Company

blobs.text:
The Group is focused on expanding its operations and gaining market share in its existing markets, where
it can address 85 million retail customers. In all the Group's target countries, e-commerce business
volume is expanding rapidly at 20% and more with Central and Eastern European countries having an
especially large expansion potential due to only a small percentage of retail customers currently shopping
online (Source: Ecommerce Europe, June 2014). For instance, in Poland, loan applications for unsecured
consumer loans in the Group's Direct Consumer Business Segment have increased from approximately
7,000 when the Group began operations in Poland in 2013 to over 116,000 applications in 2014 and to
137,000 applications in the LTM Period ended 30 June 2015. While this growth has not yet resulted in a
significant share of the Group's overall interest income, due primarily to the Group's strategic decision to
keep approval rates in Poland at a low level while it gains experience and data for scoring in this market,
the Group believes the potential in these new target countries is large.

Before the Offering described in this Prospectus, the Group was principally geared towards generating
dividends for its owners and increasing profitability. As a result, overall growth rates were limited by the
relatively small increases in the overall loan portfolio. Equity was previously paid out through dividends
and group contributions (€6.0 million in 2014, €9.7 million in 2013 and €8.6 million in 2012) and thus the
CET1 ratio was not high enough to significantly increase the overall loan portfolio at limited risk volumes
(the CET1 ratio was 12.75%, 14.66% and 13.26% in 2012, 2013 and 2014, respectively, compared to a
10.5% minimum total capital ratio (plus 1% additional buffer starting in September 2015) required by
Swedish and EU law). Following the Offering, the Group will be able to significantly increase its loan
portfolio while still maintaining a high CET1 ratio – the Group targets to maintain a CET1 ratio in line
with historic ratios. At the midpoint of the price range, the net proceeds to the Group would be €47.9
million which will increase the Group's regulatory capital for CET1 calculations (own funds) from €34.5
million (as at 30 June 2015) to €82.4 million, thus providing the Group with the flexibility to significantly
increase its loan volume.

The Group's business is deeply rooted in the Fintech business model. Real-time analysis and predictive
modeling of customers' economic capabilities is part of the Group's day-to-day business model. The
Group's management believes that the key to success in its existing markets is to balance its approach to
business between the "Fin" and the "Tech", that is to focus both on the banking part of the Group's
business and the distribution to customers through its product portfolio. The Group has employed a
strategy to diversify its product portfolio and aims to launch all its existing products in most or all its
existing target market. For instance, the Group intends to launch credit card offerings in all of its current
markets although they are currently only offered in Norway (following the acquisition of BB Finans).
Business Segments

The Group operates two separate segments (i) its direct consumer business in which it offers unsecured
loans and credit cards to retail customers directly, either through partners (e.g. mobile applications), its
own distribution channels or via point of sale physical payment terminals, and (ii) its Sales Finance & E-
Commerce Segment's business in which it offers installment loans to customers of merchants.
The Group uses its funds it receives via deposits to finance the credit volume in both its segments.
Direct Consumer Business Segment

In the Direct Consumer Business Segment, the Group offers unsecured loans and credit cards. Its loans
are offered via various distribution channels, through the Group's own websites, through partners and the
Group's sales finance invoice cross-selling marketing and through physical point of sale payment
terminals. The Group is also in the process of expanding its distribution channels, for instance by offering
credit together with its partner SafeCharge Card Services which is developing an online digital wallet and
mobile application.

The Direct Consumer Business Segment contributed 69.6% or €35.2 million to the Group's overall total
operating income in the LTM Period ended 30 June 2015. As at 30 June 2015, the Group had €139.1
million in unsecured loans outstanding in this segment with an average nominal loan amount per
approved loan of €2,055 and an average length per loan of 16 to 19 months depending on the market.

The Group offers its unsecured loans in Sweden, Finland, Estonia, Norway and Poland. Credit cards are
currently only offered in Norway through BB Finans, but the Group intends to roll out credit cards
throughout its existing markets. The Group is in the process of starting operations in the Czech Republic
and Slovakia and is analyzing the market entry in the UK, Germany, Austria, the Netherlands, Latvia and
Lithuania.

The following table provides an overview of the Group's Direct Consumer Business Segment's income
statement:
Consumer Loans

The Group offers unsecured loans to consumers. These loans are offered for up to €4,000 for single
applicants and €6,000 for joint loan applicants, with the average loan being approximately €2,000, and a
term typically ranging between 12 and 60 months. The interest rate, the length and the amount of a given
loan depends on a customer's geographic location and his or her creditworthiness. Unlike "payday" or
SMS lenders, whose products often feature extremely high effective annual interest rates, the interest rate
that the TF Bank Group charges its customers is comparable to interest rates offered by major credit card
companies. The consumer loans the Group offers are provided in real time through the Group's

proprietary "big data" IT system which provides a credit score for a loan application within seconds based
on a large number of data points (for further information, see "Overview of the Credit Scoring Process,
Delivery and Collection of Payments").

The Group's number of loan applications has steadily increased in recent years with a particularly strong
increase since 2011 due to the Group's consistent marketing efforts and geographic expansion,
particularly into Poland as shown in the following graphic (loan applications since 2007):
ended 30
June 2015

In total the Group has doubled its loan applications from 61,070 in 2007 to 138,629 in 2011. Between
2011 and 30 June 2015, as a result of the Group's geographic expansion, loan applications have nearly
tripled to 371,526 applications in the LTM Period ended 30 June 2015.

Loan application approval rates vary highly from country to country. Due to the Group's large amount of
data and long history of credit decisions in Northern Europe, the Group's approval rates for loan
applications in Sweden, Finland and Estonia range from below 10% to 65%, depending on the
sociological demographics in these regions, while the Group had approval rates of 10% and less in 2014
and 2015 in Poland.

In the past, the Group has operated and made credit decisions based on highly stringent criteria in order to
keep the ratio of non-performing loans to performing loans at a low rate. In addition, the Group was also
limited by the requirement to maintain a CET1 ratio above statutory limits and by the Company's
shareholders focus on dividends and group contributions, which partially limited its ability to grow its
loan portfolio in line with the growth in its loan applications. The Group reduced its overall approval rates
to limit its overall loan portfolio growth. This past growth limitation, despite the increase in the overall
number of applications, is also due to a conscious decision by the Group to only slowly expand loan
volumes in Poland, which is a newly entered market, despite especially high loan applications there. The
Group instead chose to build up a larger database for scoring in Poland, but intends to increase approval
rates in the future.

(Virtual) Credit Cards

In July 2015, the Group acquired the Norwegian consumer finance company BB Finans for NOK 69.6
million (€7.9 million as at 30 June 2015), which has operated in the Norwegian market for approximately
40 years under private ownership. Regulatory approval for the acquisition was granted by the Norwegian
regulatory on 19 June 2015. BB Finans has a record of successful credit offerings to consumers, primarily
via unsecured loans and credit cards and the transaction was closed in July 2015. For more information
on the terms of the acquisition of BB Finans, see "—Material Contracts."

BB Finans had nine employees as at 30 June 2015 and had both unsecured loans and credit cards
outstanding. The total loans to the public consisted of NOK 22.7 million (approximately €2.5 million)
outstanding loan balances on a total of approximately 5,000 credit cards issued to customers and
NOK 116.4 million (approximately €13 million) were outstanding on approximately 3,000 unsecured
loans issued to customers. BB Finans had over 91,000 loan applications in 2014. Its interest income
amounted to approximately NOK 25 million in 2015 (approximately €2.8 million). BB Finans issues
unsecured consumer loans up to about NOK 250,000 (approximately €28,000) and thus higher loans than
TF Bank, however the average loan outstanding as at 30 June 2015 was about €5,000 per loan. The TF
Bank Group's management anticipates that with a greater source of funding available to BB Finans from
TF Bank as well as an upgraded IT-platform, the approval rate on loans can be grown extensively in the
future.

Through its acquisition of BB Finans, the Group has expanded its product offerings to include credit cards
to consumers. The Group offers physical credit cards to consumers through various promotional offering
strategies. Typical credit limits for these cards are approximately €2,000 with average interest rates of
approximately 21%. The Group also intends to offer virtual credit cards through use of an online digital
wallet and mobile application. Customers can register for an account online for a virtual card at
www.pay.com or download the application to smart phones or tablets for use as a virtual wallet to send or
receive payments in addition to using as an electronic or virtual credit card, see "—Digital Wallet Mobile
Application" below.
DentaPay

In June 2015, BB Finans signed a partnership agreement with Odin Kapital Norway to provide credit
solutions for dental care payments. The hardware, which consists of physical payment terminals at dental
offices, as well as the software for these terminals, is provided by Odin Kapital, while BB Finans
provides the credit solution and loans to customers offered via credit cards. Approved customers sign a
credit agreement directly on the DentaPay machine.

DentaPay launched operations in June 2015 at three dental offices and initiated a further marketing
campaign in Norway in August 2015. The marketing campaign consists of direct marketing to all dentists
in Norway as well as a phone campaign. By July 2015, there were several dental offices signed up with a
total combined revenue of approximately NOK 750 million (approximately €85 million) according to the
internal calculations of BB Finans and Odin Kapital. Dentist revenue in Norway is estimated by Odin
Kapital and TF Bank Group to be in excess of NOK 7 billion (approximately €800 million) in 2014 based
on an internal market survey completed in 2014. The average expense per visit at the dentist in Norway in
a pilot launch project of DentaPay earlier in 2015 including three dentist offices (Bergen, Oslo and
Trondheim) amounted to approximately NOK 2,700 (approximately €300). Based on an internal study of
competitors in the same market, the Group's management believes that 3% to 5% of customers in Norway
will ask for installment loans to finance expenses at the dentist.

For more information on the terms of the agreement with Odin Kapital Norway, see "—Material
Contracts."
Digital Wallet Mobile Application

In June 2015, the Group signed an agreement with SafeCharge Card Services, a member of the
SafeCharge Group, to integrate a credit function into SafeCharge Card Service's online digital wallet and
mobile application. The SafeCharge Group is a global provider of payment services, technologies and risk
management solutions for online and mobile businesses. Established in 2007, the SafeCharge Group
principally concentrates on advanced payment technologies and has been listed on the London Stock
Exchange AIM market since 2014. The SafeCharge Group is principally working together with customers

from various e-commerce areas and employs over 350 people across its operations in the UK, Cyprus,
Bulgaria, Israel, Germany, Austria and Ireland.

The online "digital wallet" mobile application is offered by SafeCharge Card Services via the domain
www.pay.com where customers can download the mobile application, while TF Bank Group will help
market the application to its customers. This application can be used as a pre-paid card or loaded with
credit which is provided by the TF Bank Group. The system is based on the MasterCard payment
ecosystem. The agreement with SafeCharge Card Services grants exclusivity to TF Bank Group to
provide the unsecured credit function in Sweden, Estonia, Finland, Norway, Latvia and Lithuania with an
option to include Poland and the Czech Republic on or before 1 January 2017 if the Group has
successfully launched operations in these territories by this time. TF Bank Group is SafeCharge Card
Service's first European franchisee for its online digital wallet and mobile application. The launch of the
digital wallet mobile application is targeted for the fourth quarter of 2015 or the first quarter of 2016.

For more information on the terms of the agreement with SafeCharge Card Services, see "—Material
Contracts."
Auction Website in the Baltics

The Group is currently in discussions regarding a possible partnership agreement with one of the largest
Baltic online auction sites. This online auction site provides customers the opportunity to pay for goods
and services in its own virtual currency and the TF Bank Group is in discussions to partner with it in
order to integrate credit solutions. The online auction site has analyzed its auctions and realized that the
bidding frequency drops off over certain amounts at levels of above €200. The Group's management
believes it can increase closing rates on more valuable items by providing credits to users bidding on
larger items.
Partnership for physical payment terminals

The Group is currently negotiating a cooperation agreement with a global provider and market leader in
payment solutions and payment terminals, in order to start offering loan financing through point of sale
payment terminals in physical shopping locations in the Baltics.

The Group uses its experience with TFB Store, which it launched in 2014, for this partnership. See "—
Sales Finance & E-Commerce Segment—Point of Sale Solution" below.
Sales Finance & E-Commerce Segment
Overview

In the LTM Period ended 30 June 2015, the Sales Finance & E-Commerce Segment contributed 30.4% or
€15.4 million to the Group's total operating income. As at 30 June 2015, the Group had €38.5 million in
loans outstanding to end customers in this segment, with the average loan per customer granted in the
LTM Period ended 30 June 2015 amounting to €129 and the average length per loan, depending on the
target country, between nine and eleven months.

The Sales Finance & E-Commerce Segment was reintegrated into the Group in May 2014. Until 2007,
both of the Group's current segments were jointly operated within the same overall group (the Consortio
Fashion Group), but in 2007 Consortio Fashion Group's beneficial owners separated direct consumer
lending and sales finance. The Sales Finance & E-Commerce Segment was only integrated with the
Group as at 1 May 2014. For a description of the agreement relating to the integration of the Sales
Finance & E-Commerce Segment, see "—Material Contracts."

The Group has signed a joint venture agreement with Intrum Justitia in October 2014 to create Avarda
AB, which started initial operations in March 2015. Avarda signed up ten merchants between March 2015
and 30 June 2015 and one additional merchant between 30 June 2015 and the date of this Prospectus.

Invoice solutions for e-commerce merchants are offered in Sweden, Finland, Norway, Denmark, Estonia
and Latvia and are currently being started with the support of a merchant in Poland, the Czech Republic
and Slovakia. The Group is also analyzing the market entry in the UK, Germany, Austria, the Netherlands
and Lithuania.

The following table provides an overview of the Group's Sales Finance & E-Commerce Segment's
income statement (the year 2014 only includes the results of operations for the period from May 2014
until 31 December 2014):
erchants.
*Other operating expenses relates to commissions to mer
"White Label" Invoice Solutions

The Group generates its operating income in the Sales Finance & E-commerce Segment principally
through interest income (in 2014 the Group's APR varied between its four merchants between 27% and
30%, but are typically between 20% and 30%). In addition, the Group charges small invoice fees and
receives fees and commissions for payment default insurance from some customers applying for such
insurance. In addition, the Group charges reminder fees of typically €5 to €6 if consumers miss payments
when installments are due.

The TF Bank Group's principal product offering in the Sales Finance & E-Commerce Segment is its
flexible "plug and play" online payment solution which is tailored to merchants. This product includes
invoicing and installment terms for consumers for a particular merchant's products, encompassing
benefits for all parties involved. The following is a description of the principal elements of this product:

After an online shopper selects an item and is prompted to the check-out function on the
merchants' online shop, the choice of payment via installment loans is offered as an alternative to
traditional credit cards. The customer may choose an invoice or an account.

The invoice is designed to be paid interest free after approximately 30 days, with such initial
interest free period being extended for some merchants and markets up to 50 days. The online
shopper is thus initially only charged an invoice fee of usually €2 to €3 per invoice and provided
with an interest free loan.

If the customer chooses to open an account with the Group and finance the purchase when at the
checkout, then an installment plan is created covering up to 36 months, with the length of the
loan at the customers' discretion.

There is no penalty for early repayment of the loan; the customer can repay the loan at the end of
each month.

Customers, who choose the invoice method, may convert from their invoice payment to a loan
account with the Group after having received the invoice.

   Regardless of the choice of invoice or account, the customer will be given a credit limit based
    primarily on the item(s) purchased and the customers' ability to repay (based on the Group's
    credit assessment).

   The application for a loan is processed through the merchant's web store while the credit
    decision is made in real-time and is risk-assessed by TF Bank Group's credit origination platform
    which is integrated to the merchant's web store. The credit decision is based on the consumer's
    personal identification number (usually based on their date of birth), something that is typically
    known to the consumer in most of the Group's target markets, as well as internal and external
    data available to the Group in real time. The customer's credit card information, including the
    expiry date and the three or four digit CVV number, is therefore not needed nor divulged online.

   Invoices are sent to customers in the name of the merchant. The Group, however, may cross sell
    its own other products, such as unsecured loans and credit cards from its Direct Consumer
    Business Segment, to sales finance customers via such invoices.

The Group believes that the advantages for the merchant will drive growth for such installment loans in
the future. An online merchants receives instant liquidity (as the Group usually settles transactions on the
following bank day), improved profit margins (as the Group pays a commission to the merchant as
opposed to credit card companies, which usually charge the merchant a commission) and the opportunity
to market the merchant's brand (as the invoices are issued with the merchant's brand displayed).

Commissions paid to merchants are individually negotiated with merchants and rely on several factors,
most notably they are based on the APR of the loans that the merchants want to have charged to their
customers. Lower APRs also result in a lower share of commissions, in order to keep profit margins and
the Group's return on equity at certain levels. The Group's Sales Finance & E-Commerce Segment's
business originated from business for Haléns AB, Bubbleroom and Cellbes, three merchants which are all
part of the Consortio Fashion Group which is owned by the same beneficial owners as the TF Bank
Group. Because of this relationship, the Group's commission terms with these three merchants have been
favorable to the merchants with 50% of total operating income being paid to merchants in the LTM
Period ended in 30 June 2015. Despite this high share of income paid in commission to merchants, the TF
Bank Group was able to achieve a 28% return on business equity in the Sales Finance & E-Commerce
Segment (for a definition of return on business equity, see "Selected Financial and Operating Data").

Overview of the Credit Scoring Process, Delivery and Collection of Payments
Direct consumer loans

The Group's proprietary loan origination system ("Phoenix") collects customer data as entered by the
customer (i.e., name, address, date of birth, income, other loan commitments etc.). Phoenix is integrated
with TF Bank's own web pages in each respective market, with local online loan brokers, local credit
bureaus, external EU-determined sanction lists, TF Bank's automated in-house credit rules applicable per
market ("Credit Decision Work Flow") and external income-control sources (e.g., local tax authorities).
The integration of this information is made in real time and the lending decision for the customer
applicant is instantaneous.

When the origination process is complete, if the decision is positive Phoenix automatically exports the
data for the approved customer and the loan details to the Group's loan ledger system. Currently the
Group works with its own proprietary ledger system and also uses external banking systems where
applicable. The customer account is created and activated instantaneously and disbursements are made
through file transfers either instantaneously or at one of several various times during the same day
(depending on the market practice) directly to the customer's bank account. Time from application to loan
disbursement varies depending on the market, but is usually during the course of the same day.
E-commerce customer agreements with merchants

Upon agreement with a merchant, the Group's online function is integrated into the merchant's homepage
and a checkout function is installed offering the end consumer an invoice or repayment plan option. The
consumer, having made their choice of product online, enters their personal identification number after
which the customer's personal data is collected from internal or external sources and uploaded into the
Group's proprietary Credit Decision Work Flow. The credit decision for individual consumers is risk-
based and takes into account, among other things, the amount of the purchase and the customer's declared
or stated income level. The decision is made in real time.

In 2014, approximately 90% of applicants were approved, after which the customer is free to receive the
goods in the normal manner used by the merchant. When the purchase is confirmed, i.e., the goods are
received, an invoice is created and the debt is sold by the merchant to the Group for collection according
to the terms established for that particular sale.
Identification and credit scoring

Over the course of its operating history, the Group has developed an advanced risk-scoring model, which
is adjusted according to accessibility of customer information in different jurisdictions as well as
particular geographic trends or other outside factors which could impact lending decisions (i.e., ability
and ease with which the Group's collections process can be implemented in a certain jurisdiction). The
Group is able to collect over 8000 data points from applicants. The Group has modeled its scoring system
so that it uses a subset of this large set of information to score different loan applications. These subsets
vary depending on the market and the circumstance of loan application process and are monitored on a
constant basis. Factors that are used include key parameters such as past payment behavior, credit reports
and customer information linked to online or telephonic records.

instantaneously accept or decline an application in the vast majority of cases based on particular factors
used to make up a potential customer's credit profile, as demonstrated below:

During this process, the customer submits requested application information and the Group's automated

applicant in the case of existing customers. The Group uses this information to produce a score for
individual applicants (considering both generic scores provided by the relevant credit bureau as well as

income and personal identification, the application will receive one of three decisions: automatic
approval, conditional approval or automatic denial.
Approval rates vary between the Group's two segments:

   Direct Consumer Business Segment: Approval rates for unsecured loans in the Group's Direct

    country of application).

   Sales Finance & E-Commerce Segment: Approval rates in the Sales Finance & E-Commerce

Delivery

For the Direct Consumer Business Segment, personal loans are delivered via wire transfer to the
customer's bank account. Credit cards are delivered via registered mail.

For the Sales Finance & E-Commerce segment, the Group has individualized agreements in place with
different e-commerce merchants regarding the fulfillment of payment obligations on behalf of consumers.
Once a consumer has been approved by the Group's automated system, the merchant will immediately
fulfill the order for the customer and will collect payment from the Group according to the terms of the
individual agreement established between the Group and that particular merchant.
Collection of Payments, Sale of Non-performing Loans and Information on Loan Portfolio

The Group disposes of practically all non-performing loans which are at 69 days past due (except in
Norway and Estonia and with limited exceptions regarding the timing of disposal in other countries). The
Group believes it is achieving a comparatively high average sale price for its non-performing loans. In
2014, the Group received between 35% and 70% of the face value of non-performing assets in Sweden,
Finland and Poland.

The Group sends reminder invoices and contacts customers who fail to pay according to the initial
agreement terms in an attempt to resolve payment during the initial 69 day period. If such efforts are
unsuccessful, the Group will then terminate the contract and sell the non-performing loan to a collection
company. The Group has agreements in place with three different collection companies across the
different regions in which the Group operates. Each individual contract is negotiated and renegotiated
independently and the Group takes the market for non-performing loans into consideration when
considering credit scoring metrics and expansion efforts into new geographic regions.

The internal rating is primarily based on information provided by the customer. How the information is
used and weighted in the model is determined by an in-depth analysis of existing customers from a risk
perspective. The variables proven to best predict defaults are given a higher score in the model. The
Group is using both internal ratings and ratings provided by external providers to ensure that the risk
assessment is as accurate and precise as possible. Both ratings are performed independently but are used
together in the Group's credit assessment. The rating model is only applied to new customers, while
existing customers with a payment history and similar variables have proven to be good sources for credit
assessment.
Information Technology and Research & Development

The TF Bank Group combines standardized solutions where applicable and its own custom-made systems
when business advantages are achieved. Main processes like credit origination, loan maintenance and
datawarehousing are handled with modern in-house solutions which give the Group the flexibility to act
fast in a changing market. The IT platform is based on a Microsoft environment for both development and
hosting and the IT infrastructure is designed to minimize the risk of external "abuse" by applying
different security layers where the critical systems are located and in back-end application.
Origination Platform

The solution used for credit origination is a set of in-house systems developed since 2013. The systems
process the applications independent of each other and coordinate the application life cycle from received
purchase/loan application to the final credit decision. The aim is to have an online interaction with the
customer where credit assessment, approval, contract signing and disbursement is made instantly after a
real-time risk assessed decision.

Credit assessments are handled within the TF Bank credit engine (Credit Decision Work Flow) which
enables online follow-up and configuration of credit policies. External (respective credit bureaus) and
internal scorecards (TF Score) are combined with behavior scoring, anti-money laundering data, public
information and other information to produce a credit decision without any manual input.
Credit Maintenance Platform

TF Bank Group's credit management systems (ledger systems) are a combination of standard software
and custom made solutions. The goal is to calculate interest, late payments and produce invoices in a
standardized way. TF Bank Group operates in the pan-European market with different legal requirements
and offers different variations of credits, which necessitates the variation in the system. The Group has
focused on flexibility and local adaptations when setting up the best solution for each market regarding
client interaction, debt collection handling and product offering.
Data analysis

All relevant data from the origination and maintenance processes are regularly transferred to a central
data warehouse where full time analysts constantly work on perfecting the scoring and approval models,
including the use of regular back-testing.
Hosting

TF Bank applies a hybrid hosting solution where the main hosting partner is Pulsen AB. Pulsen AB is a
hosting company based in Sweden with more than 50 years in the hosting business. Business critical
servers are configured with redundancy in order to minimize down time. All environments are regularly
backed up and monitored on a continuous basis.

Sales funding solutions are shared between the hosting companies Pulsen AB and Basefarm AB.
Basefarm AB is a Swedish hosting company specialized in the finance area.
Commitment to Responsible Lending

Beyond compliance with the legal and regulatory frameworks governing consumer lending on the EU and
national levels, the Group is committed to its ethical principles of responsible lending. It exercises this
commitment by providing transparent contractual terms, ensuring maximum customer data security, and
treating all consumers fairly and reasonably. The Group considers this commitment to be an obligation to
its shareholders, customers and the overall industry.

The Group bases its credit decisions on a careful assessment of customer creditworthiness and strictly
excludes "payday" loans or SMS credits from its product offerings. The Group only issues credit when it
believes, on the information available to it, that the borrower can reasonably afford to repay the loan.
When processing online purchase or loan applications, the Group is committed to the highest standards of
disclosure and procedural fairness, including complete transparency of all interest, fees, and charges as
well as information regarding repayment.

Avarda Joint Venture Agreement with Intrum Justitia
Overview

On 24 October 2014, the Company and Intrum Justitia AB (Publ) entered into a joint venture agreement
(the "Joint Venture Agreement"), forming the Swedish private limited liability company of Goldcup
10363 AB (thereafter renamed to Avarda AB), to provide TF Bank Group's sales finance & e-commerce
product to online retailers in Sweden, Finland, Norway and Denmark (the "Avarda Territories"). Under
the terms of the Joint Venture Agreement, TF Bank owns a 51% stake in Avarda, with Intrum Justitia
owning 49%. Both parties provided SEK 1 million towards the initial SEK 2 million share capital of
Avarda. Each party will also contribute an aggregate of SEK 38 million (in proportion to their respective
ownership stakes) as an unconditional capital contribution, which Avarda may draw in successive
tranches. Any dividends paid out to TF Bank and Intrum Justitia will be paid out in accordance with their
shareholdings.
Contributions to the Business

To promote the business of Avarda, TF Bank provides Avarda with its e-commerce platform for use and
development in its e-commerce product offerings. While TF Bank retained the right to maintain
agreements with its existing four merchants in its sales finance business, all future online retailer clients
in the Avarda Territories are required to be clients of Avarda, for the benefit of the joint venture.

Intrum Justitia provides Avarda access to an experienced sales team and to its large customer base. In the
Joint Venture Agreement, Intrum Justitia agreed to use its reasonable best efforts to ensure that its current
and future retailer clients retain the services offered by Avarda within the Avarda Territories. Intrum
Justitia also has the right to offer collection services and purchased debt services to Avarda.

Both TF Bank and Intrum Justitia agreed not to compete with Avarda in the Avarda Territories in sales
finance as long as the Joint Venture Agreement is in existence.
Management

A managing director, to be agreed between Intrum Justitia and TF Bank handles the daily operations of
Avarda under the direction of its board of directors, which consists of four members (two nominated by
each of TF Bank and Intrum Justitia, respectively).
Funding

TF Bank agreed to provide working capital to Avarda for Avarda's loans to end customers on an as-need
basis, initially up to SEK 400 million, at a market price based on the deposit interest rate paid by TF Bank
in Sweden. In addition, TF Bank has agreed to use its reasonable best efforts to provide additional
required financing (in the form of loans) at a rate mutually beneficial for both parties.
Licensing

Currently, all of Avarda's business is conducted in the Company's name. The Company will transfer the
respective merchant agreements to the appropriate Avarda subsidiaries once Avarda has received all
necessary licenses and is in a position to be a counterparty in its own right in the respective markets in
which it will operate. Avarda has applied to the SFSA for a license to conduct operations under the
Certain Consumer Credit-related Operations Act. The application has not yet been approved due to
opinions of the SFSA regarding the currently envisioned customer credit process. The Company and
Intrum Justitia will modify this process in order to address these concerns. Avarda has separately filed a
notification requirement to the appropriate public authority in Finland and has already received a license
to operate in Finland, where a majority of the merchants it has already signed up are located. Until a
license is granted to Avarda by the SFSA, the Avarda business in Sweden can continue to be conducted
under the license of the Company.
Transfer of Shares

Should the ownership of the ultimate beneficial owners of TF Bank named in the joint venture agreement
with Intrum Justitia fall below 30% of the voting rights in TF Bank, Intrum Justitia shall have a right to
acquire all of TF Bank's shares in Avarda at a price determined by the Valuation Mechanism (as defined
below).

During the first two years of the Joint Venture Agreement, neither party may dispose of its shares without
the consent of the other. After such two year period, either TF Bank or Intrum Justitia may dispose of all
(but not part) of its shares to an independent third party provided that the other joint venture partner is
given a right of first refusal to acquire the shares at a price determined by the Valuation Mechanism, less
a 25% discount, or (if lower) the same price as the offer made by the independent third party.
Length of Agreement

The Joint Venture Agreement has an initial term of ten years, with an automatic extension of five years
thereafter.
Buy-Out Options

TF Bank may exercise a buy-out option should Avarda's assets fall below SEK 10 million during the
fourth quarter of 2016 and the first quarter of 2017.
Intrum Justitia may exercise an unconditional buy-out option from 1 January 2020 until 31 December

Under the terms of both options, the exercising party will have the right to acquire all of the other party's
shares in Avarda in accordance with a valuation based on the previous financial year (e.g. in case of
Intrum Justitia's option, for the full year 2019) (the "Valuation Mechanism"). This valuation will be
determined based on a percentage of the value of its assets plus a multiple of the amount of the profits
after tax for the preceding year. The total valuation shall not exceed the aggregate of 66% of Avarda's
Average Assets and eleven times Avarda's Profits after Tax. "Average Assets" in this context means
external lending (i.e., financial receivables originating from the operating business). "Profit after tax" may
be adjusted if there are material extraordinary items impacting profit for the relevant year and where the
tax cost applied shall be a function of a normalized tax rate based on the prevailing tax rate in the
countries contributing to taxable profit.

In the event Intrum Justitia exercises its buy-out option in 2020, TF Bank will be bound by a non-
competition agreement in the Avarda Territories for a period of two years from the date on which the
buy-out option exercised by Intrum Justitia.

REGULATION
Regulatory Environment

The Group operates in over seven jurisdictions within Europe and due to harmonized legal requirements
for credit institutions within the European Economic Area ("EEA"), the business conducted in Member
states other than Sweden is subject to similar regulations. The Company may nevertheless be subject to
certain local legislative requirements regarding how to conduct its small consumer loans business. For an
example, as at 1 June 2013, Finnish legislation has stipulated a maximum permitted actual interest rate on
small consumer loans. Monitoring of legislative developments in the countries the Group operates in,
including through the support of local legal counsels, is part of the Group's compliance monitoring
process. While the management of the Company believes the majority of the jurisdictions the Group
operates in offers stable regulatory environments for the development and administration of a functioning
consumer credit market, especially the consumer loan segment, there have been instances where
legislative changes have had a restrictive effect.

In 2014, Sweden implemented the European Banking Authority ("EBA") Guidelines on Internal
Governance (GL 44) through new regulations and general guidelines from the SFSA. The new regulations
include, inter alia, stricter requirements relating to risk management, ethical rules, control functions,
regulatory compliance, outsourcing and organizational requirements. The Company adapted new and
more comprehensive internal routines and regulations in order to ensure a proper implementation of the
above mentioned regulatory framework.

Furthermore, the implementation of CRD IV and CRR in Sweden in 2014, resulted in stricter
requirements concerning, inter alia, capital buffers, risk management and information disclosure. The
requirements led to changes in the internal capital adequacy procedures within the Company as well as
the procedures for periodic reporting to the SFSA. The Company initiated a project in order to
successfully implement the above mentioned requirements within the Group. Through this accumulated
experience in handling legislative developments, the Group has also been able to identify situations where
the continued conduct of business within a given jurisdiction would have ultimately exposed one or more
Group subsidiaries to unacceptable levels of risk. In these limited scenarios the Company's senior
management took a conscious and informed decision to wind down operations in that country. Such a
decision entails the assessment of a whole range of factors, including the identification of elevated levels
of reputational risk, the probable imposition of administrative sanctions or other penalties, potential
financial losses, the overall cost to the Group of allocating resources to adverse scenarios, rather than
focusing on growth and business expansion, as well as the overall viability of operations in that
jurisdiction.

Overview of EU and EEA Licensing Requirements

As an authorized bank within the EEA, the Company is affected by EU legislation, principally CRD IV

and licensing requirements are applicable to companies providing micro-loans.

In each jurisdiction in Europe where the Company starts operations, it completes an analysis of which
licenses, memberships and registrations are required for the business. As a Swedish bank, the Company is

Swedish Deposit Protection Program

The Swedish Deposit Protection Program is a state-provided guarantee of deposits in all types of accounts
in banks, securities companies and certain other financial institutions. The Deposit Protection Program
guarantees the customers' deposits in the event the Company is declared bankrupt or if the SFSA decides
that the Insurance shall be activated. The Deposit Protection Program is administered by the Swedish
National Debt Office, a state-controlled government agency.

If activated, the Deposit Protection Program guarantees each customer compensation amounting to the
value of the total funds on his or her account(s) with the Company plus accrued interest until the time of
the bankruptcy or the SFSA's decision. The maximum compensation is an amount (in SEK)
corresponding to €100,000.

The compensation is paid by the Swedish National Debt Office within 20 business days from the date on
which the Company was declared bankrupt or the SFSA ordered the Insurance to be activated.

Approval and Reporting Requirements of qualified shareholding in the Company

Pursuant to the Swedish Banking and Financing Business Act (Chapter 14 Section 1), a new or existing
shareholder attaining a qualified direct or indirect shareholding level of 10% or more has to be approved
by the SFSA before the consummation of the acquisition. This also applies to an increase of an existing
qualified shareholders' holding of shares, which will result in a holding of shares amounting to 20, 30 or
50 (direct and indirect shareholding in the company). The SFSA's approval is also required if the
Company becomes a subsidiary of a qualified owner.

Pursuant to the Swedish Banking and Financing Business Act (Chapter 14 Section 3), the SFSA shall be
informed in case an existing shareholder of the Company decides to divest a qualified shareholding
resulting in a decrease to 10%, 20%, 30% or 50% of such shareholder's direct or indirect holding of the
total amount of shares in the Company.

COREP Reporting: This report covers the following areas: (i) liquidity coverage ratio (LCR), (ii)
own funds and own funds requirements (CA), (iii) large exposures and concentration risk (LE),
(iv) leverage (LEVARAGE), (v) liquidity (NSFR).

The liquidity coverage ratio report is submitted on a monthly basis while the other reports are

FINREP Reporting: This new set of reporting started in October 2014 has increased the reporting
requirements to the EBA and covers a variety of new and additional financial reporting
